jor industrial city, the [[Irtysh\u2013Karaganda Canal]] was constructed in the 1960s, to supply the Karaganda metropolitan area with water from the [[Irtysh River]] more than 400&nbsp;km away.\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Religion ===\n[[File:\u0421\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e-\u0412\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|[[Russian Orthodox Church]] in Karaganda]]\n[[File:\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0435\u0442\u044c.jpg|thumb|[[Islam in Kazakhstan|Mosque]] in Karaganda]]\nThe city is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Karaganda]].\n\n=== Theater ===\nThe [[:ru:\u0414\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0446 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043d\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0432 (\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430)|Miners Palace of Culture]] is a major landmark in Karaganda.\n\n=== Sports ===\n[[File:Dusan Petronijevic.jpg|thumb|[[FC Shakhter Karagandy]] players]]\n[[FC Shakhter Karagandy]] is a football club based in [[Shakhtyor Stadium (Karagandy)|Shakhtyor Stadium]]. They are the current champions of the [[Kazakhstan Premier League]]. The local football club has its own heroes and big accomplishments. The most popular player in the team is Andrey Finonchenko. The biggest accomplishment is a victory against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] from Scotland. The score was 2-0. The city participated in the open Kazakh Cup in [[bandy]] 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=https://www.sports.kz/news/v-petropavlovske-startoval-otkryityiy-kubok-rk-po-hokkeyu-s-myachom|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.co.uk|accessdate=Apr 14, 2019}}</ref> [[Saryarka Karagandy]] is an ice hockey team that plays in the Russian-based [[Supreme Hockey League]] (VHL) The popularity of winter sports is growing each year and multi-sports winter games are organised for the [[Qaraghandy Region]].<ref>[http://caspionet.kz/eng/sport/Winter_Sports_Tournaments_begin_in_Karaganda_1328938863.html Winter Sports Tournaments begin in Karaganda] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120707124308/http://caspionet.kz/eng/sport/Winter_Sports_Tournaments_begin_in_Karaganda_1328938863.html |date=2012-07-07 }}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n* [[Qaraghandy Zoo]]\n\n=== Education ===\n* [[Karaganda State Tehnical University]]\n* [[Karaganda State University]]\n* [[Qaraghandy State Medical University|Karaganda State Medical University]]\n\n=== Other ===\n\nKaraganda was often used as the punchline in a popular joke in the former [[Soviet Union]]. Karaganda is fairly isolated in a vast area of uninhabited [[steppe]], and is thought by many to be \"the middle of nowhere\". When used in the [[locative case]] (\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435), the final syllable rhymes with the Russian word for \"where\" (\u0433\u0434\u0435), as well as with a Russian obscenity used to answer to an unwanted question \"Where?\". Thus the exchange: \"\u0413\u0434\u0435?\" \u2014 \"\u0412 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435!\" (\"Where is it?\" \u2014 \"In Karaganda!\")\n\n== Transport ==\n[[Sary-Arka Airport]] is 20 kilometers south-east of the city.\n\n== Notable residents ==\n[[File:Osaka07 D8A Decathlon Karpov.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Russians in Kazakhstan|Russian Kazakhstani]] athlete [[Dmitriy Karpov]]]]\n* [[Nurken Abdirov]], Soviet [[World War II]] pilot and [[Hero of the Soviet Union]]. A statue in Abdirov's honor is in the center of the city.\n* [[Anjelika Akbar]], pianist\n* [[Toktar Aubakirov]], former [[cosmonaut]] ([[Soyuz TM-13]]) and member of Kazakhstan parliament\n* [[Boris Avrukh]], chess [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]]\n* [[Konstantin Engel]], professional football player\n*[[Gennady Golovkin]], boxer, former [[World Boxing Association|WBA]], [[World Boxing Council|WBC]], [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] and [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] Middleweight Champion, holds the greatest knockout ratio in middleweight championship history and silver medalist in the ([[2004 Summer Olympics]])\n* [[Akhmad Kadyrov]], former President of the [[Chechen Republic]]\n* [[Dimitri Kotschnew]], professional ice hockey player\n* [[Andrei Krukov]], Olympic figure skater ([[1998 Winter Olympics]])\n* [[Juri Litvinov]], Olympic figure skater (1998 Winter Olympics) and national champion\n* [[Aslan Maskhadov]], third President, [[Chechen Republic of Ichkeria]]\n* [[Valery Oisteanu]], writer, photographer, and performance artist\n* [[Aleksandr Shustov]], gold medal-winning high jumper\n* [[Dmitriy Karpov]], bronze medal-winning decathlon and heptathlon athlete ([[2004 Summer Olympics]])\n* [[Aleksei Grigorievich Stakhanov]], Director of Number 31 mine (1943-1957) and [[Hero of the Soviet Union]] as a folk hero mine worker with 14 times quota production\n* [[Pavel Vorobiev]], professional ice hockey player\n* [[Joseph Werth]], Bishop of Transfiguration, [[Novosibirsk, Russia]]\n* Katia Ivanova, glamour model, reality TV star, UK Celebrity Big Brother contestant 2009 (born in Karaganda in 1988)\n\n== Sister cities ==\n* {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[Songpa-gu]], [[South Korea]] (since 1994)\n* {{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[Kamianske]], [[Ukraine]]\n* {{flagicon|Iran}} [[Arak, Iran|Arak]], [[Iran]] (since 2008)\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Karlag]]\n*[[Karaganda Region]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Karaganda}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110826231635/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/106.1/ah000017.html Kate Brown, Gridded Lives: Why Kazakhstan and Montana are nearly the same place]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120624044550/http://www.karagandy.aero/ www.karagandy.aero] Karagandy International Airport\n* [http://www.world66.com/asia/centralasia/kazakhstan/karagandy www.world66.com] Karagandy Travel Guide \n* [http://visitkazakhstan.kz/en/guide/places/view/568/ visitkazakhstan.kz] Monuments of Karagandy\n* [http://www.worldplaces.net/kgz/00/karagandy/  www.worldplaces.net/kgz/00/karagandy/ ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130215040804/http://kazakhstan.usembassy.gov/media-032612.html usembassy.gov] Media Advisory: Karagandy Eco-Museum and Nevada Test Site Historical Foundation Project Opening\n* [http://www.accuweather.com/en/kz/karagandy/222471/weather-forecast/222471  www.accuweather.com] Karagandy Weather Forecast\n* [http://www.forecast.co.uk/karagandy.html forecast.co.uk]  Karagandy Weather Forecast  \n* [http://www.weather-forecast.com/locations/Karagandy/forecasts/latest weather-forecast.com]  Karagandy Weather Forecast \n* [http://www.gismeteo.com/city/daily/14400/ gismeteo.com] Karagandy Weather Forecast\n\n{{Karaganda Region}}\n{{Cities of Kazakhstan}}\n\n[[Category:Karaganda| ]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Kazakhstan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Karaganda Region]]\n[[Category:Cities in Central Asia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: Bronze age \u2192 Bronze Age, \u2019s \u2192 's, 2-0 \u2192 2\u20130", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karaganda"}
{"title_page": "Shambuka", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Rama kill shambuka.jpg  |thumb|Rama slays Shambuka.]]\n'''Shambuka''' ([[IAST]]: \u015bamb\u016bka) is, in [[Hindu mythology]], a character in some versions of the [[Ramayana]]. According to that version, Shambuka, a [[shudra]] ascetic, was slain by [[Rama]] for attempting to perform penance. This act of Shambuka was perceived by Rama as the act in violation of [[dharma]] as he believed that the bad [[karma]], resulting from this act, caused the death of a [[Brahmin]]'s son in his kingdom.<ref>Government of Maharashtra, ''Nasik District Gazeteer: History - Ancient Period'' {{cite web |url=http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/nasik/005%20History/001%20AncientPeriod.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107163101/http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/nasik/005%20History/001%20AncientPeriod.htm |archivedate=7 November 2006 |df=dmy-all }} (text credited to Mahamahopadhyaya Dr. V. V. Mirashi)</ref>\nBut there is no character named Shambuka in Valmiki & others versions of Ramayan.\n\n== Story ==\n\nFollowing is the English translation of chapter 73\u201376 done by Hari Prasad Shastri in his book \"The Ramayana of Valmiki: Translated by Hari Prasad Shastri\".<ref name=\"sc2001\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/The.Ramayana.of.Valmiki.by.Hari.Prasad.Shastri|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki|author=Hari Prasad Shastri|publisher=Shanti Sadan|year=1957|isbn=978-0-8542-4048-7|pages=1585}}</ref>\n\n{{Quotation|An aged peasant, a brahmin, bearing his dead child in his arms came to the palace gate, weeping and crying out again and again \u201cWhat sin did I commit in a previous existence?\" Overcome with paternal grief, he repeated \u201cO My Son, My Son! Ah! Of what fault was I formerly guilty in another body that I should see mine only son meet with death ? This boy had not yet reached adolescence, his fourteenth year not having been completed! To my misfortune, before his time, this dear child has been struck down by death! In a few days, I and thy mother too will die of grief, O Dear Child! I do not recollect ever to have uttered a lie; I do not remember ever inflicting an injury on any animal or doing harm to any person! People perish under the unrighteous rule of an impious monarch. The evil conduct of a king brings about the premature death of his subjects. When, in the cities and country, crimes are committed and no supervision is exercised, then death is to be feared! Undoubtedly the king will be held to be at fault in city and country, hence the death of this child.\" Such were the countless recriminations that the unfortunate father addressed to the king whilst he clasped his son to his breast. The piteous lamentations of that unfortunate brahmin reached the ears of the king and he, in the profound distress, called together his ministers, Vasishtha and Vamadeva, with his brothers and the elders of the city also. Then eight brahmins were ushered into the king's presence by Vasishtha, who resembled a God, and they said \"May prosperity attend thee!\" Thereafter those foremost of the Twice-born, Markandeya, Maudgajya, Vamadeva, Kashyapa, Katyayana, Javali, Gautama and Narada took their seats, and those Rishis being assembled, Rama paid obeisance to them with joined palms. Then the ministers and citizens received a cordial welcome, as was fitting, and all those highly effulgent persons being seated near him, Raghava informed them of the reproaches of that Twice-born One. Hearing the words of the prince, who was fined with distress, Narada himself made this memorable reply in the assembly of the Sages \u201cLearn, O King, what has caused the untimely death of this child! When thou art conversant therewith, do what thou considerest to be thy duty ! O Prince, Joy of the Raghus, formerly in the Krita Yuga, the brahmins alone practiced asceticism; he who was not a brahmin in no wise undertook it. At the close of that age, all was consumed and absorbed into Brahman. Thereafter the 5 brahmins were re-born enlightened and endowed with the gift of immortality. In that age, none died prematurely and all were wise. The Treta Yuga followed when the sons of Manu were born, one who practiced austerities; these noble men were the rulers, and full of power and heroism. In that era, Brahmins and Kshatriyas were equal in power nor could any distinction be found amongst them; it was then that the four castes were established. In the Treta Yuga, brahmins and warriors practiced asceticism and the rest were under the supreme obligation of obedience, proper to the Vaishya and Shudra classes; the Shudras' duty being to serve the other three. O Great King, in the Dwapara Yuga, untruth and evil increased, unrighteousness having placed a second foot on the earth, and then the Vaishyas began to practice penance, so that dharma, in the form of asceticism, was performed by the three castes, but the Shudras were not permitted to undertake it during that time, O Foremost of Men. O Prince, a man of the lowest caste may not give himself up to penance in the Dwapara Yuga; it is only in the Kali Yuga that the practice of asceticism is permitted to the Shudra caste. During the Dwapara Yuga it is a great crime for one of Shudra birth to perform such practices. At this time, in thine empire, a rigid penance is being undertaken by a wretched Shudra, O Prince, and this is the cause of the death of that child. An act of mortification that is prescribed is well done and a sixth of the merit goes to the king who rules with justice. But how should he, who does not protect his people, enjoy the sixth portion? O Lion among Men, thou should investigate the happenings in thy kingdom and put down evil wherever it is practised, so righteousness may flourish, man's life be prolonged and the child be revived.\" Rama makes a Tour of Inspection of his Kingdom hearing the nectar-like words of Narada, Rama was delighted and said to Lakshmana \u201cO Dear Friend, thou who art faithful to thy vows, go and console that leading brahmin and cause the body of the child to be placed in a jar of oil with precious unguents and fragrant salves so that it is covered and does not suffer decomposition. Act in such a way that the body of the child does not dissolve or decay.\" Having issued this command to Lakshmana, who was endowed with auspicious marks, the highly illustrious Kakutstha thought of Pushpaka, and said \u201cCome hither!\" Conscious of his intention, the golden chariot appeared before him in the same hour and bowing, said to him \u201cBehold, I am here at thy service, O Long-armed Prince! Listening to the gracious words of Pushpaka, Rama paid obeisance to the great Rishis and ascended the chariot. Armed with his bow, his two quivers and his glittering sword, Raghava left the city in the charge of his two brothers, Saumitri and Bharata, and thereafter that monarch directed his course to the western region which he explored on every side; then he went to the northern region bounded by the Himalayas, but found no one. No trace of evil-doing there; later the eastern region was carefully searched by him and that long-armed Prince, from on high in his chariot, beheld people of pure morals there, as stainless as a mirror. \nThen he, who causes felicity to the great Rishis, ranged the southern region and, on the side of the Shaivaja Mountain, a vast lake appeared to him, on the banks of which the blessed Raghava beheld an ascetic practicing an extremely rigorous penance, his head hanging downwards. On this that Prince approached the one who had given himself up to rigorous practices and said \"Blessed art thou, O Ascetic, who art faithful to thy vows ! From what caste art thou sprung, O Thou who hast grown old in mortification and who art established in heroism. I am interested in this matter, I, Rama, the son of Dasaratha. What purpose hast thou in view? Is it heaven or some other object? What boon dost thou seek by means of this hard penance? I wish to know what thou desire in performing these austerities, oh Ascetic. May prosperity attend thee! Art thou a brahmin ? Art thou an invincible Kshatriya? Art thou a Vaishya, one of the third caste or art thou a Shudra? Answer me truthfully!\" Then the ascetic, who was hanging head downwards, thus questioned by Rama, revealed his origin to that Prince born of Dasaratha, the foremost of kings, and the reason why he was practicing penance. Hearing the words of Rama of imperishable exploits, that ascetic, his head still hanging downwards, answered \"O Rama, I was born of a Shudra alliance and I am performing this rigorous penance in order to acquire the status of a God in this body. I am not telling a lie, O Rama, I wish to attain the Celestial Region. Know that I am a Shudra and my name is Shambuka.\" As he was yet speaking, Raghava, drawing his brilliant and stainless sword from its scabbard, cut off his head. The Shudra being slain, all the Gods and their leaders with Agni's followers, cried out, \u201cWell done! Well done!\" overwhelming Rama with praise, and a rain of celestial flowers of divine fragrance fell on all sides, scattered by Vayu. In their supreme satisfaction, the Gods said to that hero, Rama \u201cThou hast protected the interests of the Gods, O Highly Intelligent Prince, now ask a boon, O Beloved Offspring of Raghu, Destroyer of Thy Foes. By thy grace, this Shudra will not be able to attain heaven!\"|The Ramayana of Valmiki: Translated by Hari Prasad Shastri p1585|<ref name=sc2001/>}}\n\n== Criticism and apologetics ==\n\nHindu authors adopt other means to explain the reason behind Rama's killing of Shambuka. The [[Pushtimarg]] [[Vaishnav]]ite tradition points out that the Ramayana refers to other Shudras, such as [[Shabari]], who lived in the forest.  Shambuka therefore deliberately violated dharma in order to get Rama's attention, and attained salvation when he was beheaded.<ref>Motiramji Sastri, ''Ramayan'' (in Gujarati) (Ahmedabad, 1961).</ref>   The celebrated [[Kannada]] poet [[Kuvempu]], in his play ''Shudra Tapasvi'' shows Rama as having to both carry out his duty by punishing Shambuka, and simultaneously protect Shambuka, as a pious and devout sage, from persecution, and thereby turns the story into a critique of Brahminical attitudes and a defense of Rama.<ref>'M. Raghava, \"[http://www.hindu.com/lf/2004/10/26/stories/2004102615010200.htm The king and the protector of the devout]\" ''The Hindu'' (26 October 2004).</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.valmikiramayan.net\n\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Characters in the Ramayana]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Rama kill shambuka.jpg  |thumb|Rama slays Shambuka.]]\n'''Shambuka''' ([[IAST]]: \u015bamb\u016bka) is, in [[Hindu mythology]], a character in some versions of the [[Ramayana]]. According to that version, Shambuka, a [[shudra]] ascetic, was slain by [[Rama]] for attempting to perform penance. This act of Shambuka was perceived by Rama as the act in violation of [[dharma]] as he believed that the bad [[karma]], resulting from this act, caused the death of a [[Brahmin]]'s son in his kingdom.<ref>Government of Maharashtra, ''Nasik District Gazeteer: History - Ancient Period'' {{cite web |url=http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/nasik/005%20History/001%20AncientPeriod.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107163101/http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/nasik/005%20History/001%20AncientPeriod.htm |archivedate=7 November 2006 |df=dmy-all }} (text credited to Mahamahopadhyaya Dr. V. V. Mirashi)</ref>\n\nThe killing of Shambuka appears in the 'Uttarakanda' [Final Chapter], sargas 73-76, in the [[Valmiki Ramayana]].<ref name=\"sc20012\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/The.Ramayana.of.Valmiki.by.Hari.Prasad.Shastri|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki|author=Hari Prasad Shastri|publisher=Shanti Sadan|year=1957|isbn=978-0-8542-4048-7|pages=1585}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=c-p9Iyk3lpkC&pg=PA111|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki|author=Paula Richman|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2008|isbn=9780253219534|pages=111}}</ref> \n\nNotable scholars such as Purushottama Candra Jaina,<ref>''P. 16 Labour in Ancient India'' By Purushottama Candra Jaina</ref> and John Brockington<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Rama-Steadfast-Ramayana-Penguin-Classics/dp/014044744X</ref> write that this story \"''is of late origin''\".\n\n== Story ==\n\nFollowing is the English translation of chapter 73\u201376 done by Hari Prasad Shastri in his book \"The Ramayana of Valmiki: Translated by Hari Prasad Shastri\".<ref name=\"sc2001\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/The.Ramayana.of.Valmiki.by.Hari.Prasad.Shastri|title=The Ramayana of Valmiki|author=Hari Prasad Shastri|publisher=Shanti Sadan|year=1957|isbn=978-0-8542-4048-7|pages=1585}}</ref>\n\n{{Quotation|An aged peasant, a brahmin, bearing his dead child in his arms came to the palace gate, weeping and crying out again and again \u201cWhat sin did I commit in a previous existence?\" Overcome with paternal grief, he repeated \u201cO My Son, My Son! Ah! Of what fault was I formerly guilty in another body that I should see mine only son meet with death ? This boy had not yet reached adolescence, his fourteenth year not having been completed! To my misfortune, before his time, this dear child has been struck down by death! In a few days, I and thy mother too will die of grief, O Dear Child! I do not recollect ever to have uttered a lie; I do not remember ever inflicting an injury on any animal or doing harm to any person! People perish under the unrighteous rule of an impious monarch. The evil conduct of a king brings about the premature death of his subjects. When, in the cities and country, crimes are committed and no supervision is exercised, then death is to be feared! Undoubtedly the king will be held to be at fault in city and country, hence the death of this child.\" Such were the countless recriminations that the unfortunate father addressed to the king whilst he clasped his son to his breast. The piteous lamentations of that unfortunate brahmin reached the ears of the king and he, in the profound distress, called together his ministers, Vasishtha and Vamadeva, with his brothers and the elders of the city also. Then eight brahmins were ushered into the king's presence by Vasishtha, who resembled a God, and they said \"May prosperity attend thee!\" Thereafter those foremost of the Twice-born, Markandeya, Maudgajya, Vamadeva, Kashyapa, Katyayana, Javali, Gautama and Narada took their seats, and those Rishis being assembled, Rama paid obeisance to them with joined palms. Then the ministers and citizens received a cordial welcome, as was fitting, and all those highly effulgent persons being seated near him, Raghava informed them of the reproaches of that Twice-born One. Hearing the words of the prince, who was fined with distress, Narada himself made this memorable reply in the assembly of the Sages \u201cLearn, O King, what has caused the untimely death of this child! When thou art conversant therewith, do what thou considerest to be thy duty ! O Prince, Joy of the Raghus, formerly in the Krita Yuga, the brahmins alone practiced asceticism; he who was not a brahmin in no wise undertook it. At the close of that age, all was consumed and absorbed into Brahman. Thereafter the 5 brahmins were re-born enlightened and endowed with the gift of immortality. In that age, none died prematurely and all were wise. The Treta Yuga followed when the sons of Manu were born, one who practiced austerities; these noble men were the rulers, and full of power and heroism. In that era, Brahmins and Kshatriyas were equal in power nor could any distinction be found amongst them; it was then that the four castes were established. In the Treta Yuga, brahmins and warriors practiced asceticism and the rest were under the supreme obligation of obedience, proper to the Vaishya and Shudra classes; the Shudras' duty being to serve the other three. O Great King, in the Dwapara Yuga, untruth and evil increased, unrighteousness having placed a second foot on the earth, and then the Vaishyas began to practice penance, so that dharma, in the form of asceticism, was performed by the three castes, but the Shudras were not permitted to undertake it during that time, O Foremost of Men. O Prince, a man of the lowest caste may not give himself up to penance in the Dwapara Yuga; it is only in the Kali Yuga that the practice of asceticism is permitted to the Shudra caste. During the Dwapara Yuga it is a great crime for one of Shudra birth to perform such practices. At this time, in thine empire, a rigid penance is being undertaken by a wretched Shudra, O Prince, and this is the cause of the death of that child. An act of mortification that is prescribed is well done and a sixth of the merit goes to the king who rules with justice. But how should he, who does not protect his people, enjoy the sixth portion? O Lion among Men, thou should investigate the happenings in thy kingdom and put down evil wherever it is practised, so righteousness may flourish, man's life be prolonged and the child be revived.\" Rama makes a Tour of Inspection of his Kingdom hearing the nectar-like words of Narada, Rama was delighted and said to Lakshmana \u201cO Dear Friend, thou who art faithful to thy vows, go and console that leading brahmin and cause the body of the child to be placed in a jar of oil with precious unguents and fragrant salves so that it is covered and does not suffer decomposition. Act in such a way that the body of the child does not dissolve or decay.\" Having issued this command to Lakshmana, who was endowed with auspicious marks, the highly illustrious Kakutstha thought of Pushpaka, and said \u201cCome hither!\" Conscious of his intention, the golden chariot appeared before him in the same hour and bowing, said to him \u201cBehold, I am here at thy service, O Long-armed Prince! Listening to the gracious words of Pushpaka, Rama paid obeisance to the great Rishis and ascended the chariot. Armed with his bow, his two quivers and his glittering sword, Raghava left the city in the charge of his two brothers, Saumitri and Bharata, and thereafter that monarch directed his course to the western region which he explored on every side; then he went to the northern region bounded by the Himalayas, but found no one. No trace of evil-doing there; later the eastern region was carefully searched by him and that long-armed Prince, from on high in his chariot, beheld people of pure morals there, as stainless as a mirror. \nThen he, who causes felicity to the great Rishis, ranged the southern region and, on the side of the Shaivaja Mountain, a vast lake appeared to him, on the banks of which the blessed Raghava beheld an ascetic practicing an extremely rigorous penance, his head hanging downwards. On this that Prince approached the one who had given himself up to rigorous practices and said \"Blessed art thou, O Ascetic, who art faithful to thy vows ! From what caste art thou sprung, O Thou who hast grown old in mortification and who art established in heroism. I am interested in this matter, I, Rama, the son of Dasaratha. What purpose hast thou in view? Is it heaven or some other object? What boon dost thou seek by means of this hard penance? I wish to know what thou desire in performing these austerities, oh Ascetic. May prosperity attend thee! Art thou a brahmin ? Art thou an invincible Kshatriya? Art thou a Vaishya, one of the third caste or art thou a Shudra? Answer me truthfully!\" Then the ascetic, who was hanging head downwards, thus questioned by Rama, revealed his origin to that Prince born of Dasaratha, the foremost of kings, and the reason why he was practicing penance. Hearing the words of Rama of imperishable exploits, that ascetic, his head still hanging downwards, answered \"O Rama, I was born of a Shudra alliance and I am performing this rigorous penance in order to acquire the status of a God in this body. I am not telling a lie, O Rama, I wish to attain the Celestial Region. Know that I am a Shudra and my name is Shambuka.\" As he was yet speaking, Raghava, drawing his brilliant and stainless sword from its scabbard, cut off his head. The Shudra being slain, all the Gods and their leaders with Agni's followers, cried out, \u201cWell done! Well done!\" overwhelming Rama with praise, and a rain of celestial flowers of divine fragrance fell on all sides, scattered by Vayu. In their supreme satisfaction, the Gods said to that hero, Rama \u201cThou hast protected the interests of the Gods, O Highly Intelligent Prince, now ask a boon, O Beloved Offspring of Raghu, Destroyer of Thy Foes. By thy grace, this Shudra will not be able to attain heaven!\"|The Ramayana of Valmiki: Translated by Hari Prasad Shastri p1585|<ref name=sc2001/>}}\n\n== Criticism and apologetics ==\n\nHindu authors adopt other means to explain the reason behind Rama's killing of Shambuka. The [[Pushtimarg]] [[Vaishnav]]ite tradition points out that the Ramayana refers to other Shudras, such as [[Shabari]], who lived in the forest.  Shambuka therefore deliberately violated dharma in order to get Rama's attention, and attained salvation when he was beheaded.<ref>Motiramji Sastri, ''Ramayan'' (in Gujarati) (Ahmedabad, 1961).</ref>   The celebrated [[Kannada]] poet [[Kuvempu]], in his play ''Shudra Tapasvi'' shows Rama as having to both carry out his duty by punishing Shambuka, and simultaneously protect Shambuka, as a pious and devout sage, from persecution, and thereby turns the story into a critique of Brahminical attitudes and a defense of Rama.<ref>'M. Raghava, \"[http://www.hindu.com/lf/2004/10/26/stories/2004102615010200.htm The king and the protector of the devout]\" ''The Hindu'' (26 October 2004).</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.valmikiramayan.net\n\n{{HinduMythology}}\n\n[[Category:Characters in the Ramayana]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4043:48e:ae0a:60a9:9a12:5b09:f63d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shambuka"}
{"title_page": "History of Kansas City Chiefs quarterbacks", "text_new": "{{For|a complete list of starting quarterbacks by season|List of Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterbacks}}\n[[File:Alex Smith 2014 Pro Bowl.jpg|thumb|upright|Former Chiefs quarterback Alex Smith at the 2014 Pro Bowl]]\n31 [[quarterbacks]] have started for the [[National Football League]]'s [[Kansas City Chiefs]] since their franchise began. The team has also had numerous backup quarterbacks that have stolen the spotlight from the starters.<ref name=\"Thinking\">{{cite web | title=Thinking about quarterbacks| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2003/09/12/thinking_about_quarterbacks | date=2003-09-12 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203515/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2003/09/12/thinking_about_quarterbacks |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Controversy\">{{cite web | title=Quarterbacks and controversy| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/11/01/gretz_quarterbacks__controversy/ | date=2006-11-01 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200842/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/11/01/gretz_quarterbacks__controversy/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nUnder [[Len Dawson]], the Texans/Chiefs won three [[American Football League]] championships and appeared in two [[Super Bowl]] championship games. Dawson was named [[Super Bowl MVP|Most Valuable Player]] following the Chiefs' victory in [[Super Bowl IV]]. Dawson played a total of 13 seasons with Kansas City and retired with many franchise records. Despite having little success in developing and drafting a quality quarterback of their own, the Chiefs have achieved success under many veteran quarterbacks, including [[Dave Krieg]], [[Joe Montana]], [[Elvis Grbac]], [[Trent Green]] and [[Alex Smith]]. The Chiefs have often relied on veteran leadership at the position.<ref name=\"Althaus 167\">Althaus, p. 167</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs' next hope\">{{cite web | title=Cassel is Chiefs' next hope | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3954904 | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2009-03-06 | accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> It wasn't until 2017 the Chiefs were able to successfully draft and groom a quarterback of their own, [[Patrick_Mahomes|Patrick Mahomes]], who brought them their first [[AFC_Championship_Game|AFC Championship]] title and second Super Bowl victory.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Starting quarterbacks ===\nThe Chiefs have had many notable and established quarterbacks on their squad at different times. Hall of Famers [[Len Dawson]] and [[Joe Montana]] led the Chiefs in two successful eras and both led the team to playoff appearances in their first seasons.<ref name=\"1962 Texans\">{{cite web | title=1962 Dallas Texans season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1962.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"1993 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=1993 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1993.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise's first starter was [[Cotton Davidson]], who started 25 games for the Texans before being traded in 1962.<ref name=\"Davidson\">{{cite web | title=Cotton Davidson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DaviCo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Team owner [[Lamar Hunt]] traded Davidson to the [[Oakland Raiders]] for the first-overall selection in the [[American Football League Draft|1963 AFL Draft]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/07/06/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history7/ | archive-url=https://archive.is/20070502213724/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/07/06/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history7/ | url-status=dead | archive-date=2007-05-02 | date=2007-07-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The franchise used that pick to select future Hall of Fame [[defensive tackle]] [[Buck Buchanan]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/>\n\nIn Davidson's absence, free agent quarterback [[Len Dawson]] signed with the team on July 2, 1962 after spending a five-year career in the NFL with [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] and [[Cleveland Browns|Cleveland]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> In Dallas, Dawson was rejoined with head coach [[Hank Stram]] who served as an assistant coach with [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]], where Dawson played college football.<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> In his first season with the Texans, Dawson led the team to a double-overtime victory over the [[Houston Oilers]] in the [[American Football League playoffs|AFL Championship Game]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> The victory brought the team's first league championship.\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  =\"'Lenny the Cool'...He was our leader. He was the man.\"<ref name=\"Althaus 6\"/>\n | source = \u2014 [[Buck Buchanan]], Chiefs defensive end (1963&ndash;1975).\n | width  =33%\n | align  =right\n}}\n\nLen Dawson was the franchise's most successful quarterback, playing in 182 regular season games (158 starts) for the Texans/Chiefs, and holds many franchise records.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/08/10/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history12/ | date=2007-08-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070502213724/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/08/10/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history12/ | archivedate=2007-05-02 }}</ref> He was nicknamed \"Lenny the Cool\" for his calm composure on the field.<ref name=\"Althaus 6\">Althaus, p. 6</ref><ref name=\"Althaus 1\">Althaus, p. 1</ref> Dawson completed 2,115 of 3,696 passes for 28,507&nbsp;yards with 237 touchdowns and 178 interceptions, good for an 82.6 career rating. He ranks first in team history in pass attempts, completions, passing yards and touchdowns.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> He led the Chiefs to 94 regular season wins and three AFL titles.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson led the Chiefs to an appearance in [[Super Bowl I|the first AFL&ndash;NFL Championship Game]] (later known as \"Super Bowl I\") against the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> He was named [[Super Bowl MVP|MVP]] of [[Super Bowl IV]] when he directed Kansas City to a 23&ndash;7 victory over the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson was named to six AFL All-Star teams and one [[Pro Bowl]] squad, in addition to being named the AFL Player of the Year in 1962.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson was also named the [[Walter Payton Man of the Year|NFL Man of the Year]] in [[1973 NFL season|1973]].<ref name=\"Dawson\">{{cite web | title=Len Dawson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DawsLe00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Dawson threw a franchise record six touchdown passes against the [[Denver Broncos]] on November 1, 1964 in a 49&ndash;39 victory.<ref name=\"This Week, Nov 2, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ | date=2007-11-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204195508/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ |archivedate = December 4, 2007 }}</ref> In 1966, while still playing for the Chiefs, Dawson became the sports director and anchor for [[KMBC-TV]], a local Kansas City [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate.<ref name=\"Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV\">{{cite web | title=Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV News Team Story | url=http://www.kmbc.com/kmbcnewsteam/276477/detail.html | publisher=KMBC.com | accessdate=2009-02-15 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202063010/http://www.kmbc.com/kmbcnewsteam/276477/detail.html | archivedate=2008-12-02 }}</ref> As of 2009, Dawson is still KMBC's sports director.<ref name=\"Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV\"/> He would practice and play for the Chiefs during the day and later help anchor news broadcasts at night.<ref name=\"Althaus 3\"/> After retiring from the NFL in 1975,<ref name=\"Great ones\">{{cite web|title=Great ones hard to find |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/04/great_ones_hard_to_find/ |last=Gretz |first=Bob |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-03-04 |accessdate=2009-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309132730/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/04/great_ones_hard_to_find |archivedate=March 9, 2009 }}</ref> Dawson began hosting ''[[Inside the NFL]]'' on HBO and worked network broadcasts for [[NBC]].<ref name=\"Althaus 3\">Althaus, p. 3</ref> He joined the Chiefs' radio broadcast team in 1984 and provides color commentary to game broadcasts.<ref name=\"Althaus 3\"/>\n\n[[Bill Kenney]] was the team's starting quarterback in various times between 1980 and 1988 and compiled a 46&ndash;51 record.<ref name=\"Althaus 166\">Althaus, p. 166</ref> Kenney played behind a porous offensive line and holds the franchise record for most times [[quarterback sack|sacked]] (195).<ref name=\"Althaus 166\"/> Kenney's All-Pro wide receiver teammate [[Carlos Carson]] said, \"I don't care who you are, it's tough to throw a pass when you're lying on your back.\"<ref name=\"Althaus 166\"/> Kenney was selected to the [[1984 Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> After retiring from professional football, Kenney became a [[State Senator]] for the [[Missouri Senate]].\n\nThe Chiefs made a mistake in drafting quarterback [[Todd Blackledge]] in the [[1983 NFL Draft]] believing that Blackledge was a better choice than [[Jim Kelly]] and [[Dan Marino]].<ref name=\"Althaus 167\"/><ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> Blackledge never started a full season for Kansas City while Kelly and Marino played Hall of Fame careers.<ref name=\"Warrick\">{{cite web | title=Warrick, Klinger fell way short in Cincy | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/news/story?id=3326109 | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2008-04-16 | accessdate=2009-01-16}}</ref> Blackledge started 24 total games in Kansas City, but inconsistent play led to him sharing time with [[Bill Kenney]] from 1984&ndash;1987.<ref name=\"Warrick\"/><ref name=\"Blackledge\">{{cite web | title=Todd Blackledge | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BlacTo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1987 season, the Chiefs used five starting quarterbacks for the only time in franchise history.<ref name=\"History 80s\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Chiefs History&ndash;1980's | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/ | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501122552/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/ |archivedate = May 1, 2008}}</ref> Doug Hudson was the last quarterback drafted by the team to start a game until [[Brodie Croyle]] started in 2007.<ref name=\"Huard out\"/> In Hudson's only game, he was [[Quarterback sack|sacked]] in the endzone for a [[Safety (American football score)|safety]] by the [[Denver Broncos]]' [[Jim Ryan (American football)|Jim Ryan]].<ref name=\"October 18, 1987\">{{cite web | title=Denver Broncos at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 October 18, 1987 | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/198710180kan.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The sack and fumble is the only recorded statistic for his career.<ref name=\"Hudson\">{{cite web | title=Doug Hudson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HudsDo20.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the Chiefs traded two draft selections and [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] [[Mark Robinson (American football)|Mark Robinson]] to the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in exchange for veteran quarterback [[Steve DeBerg]].<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/04/this_week_in_chiefs_history6/ | date=2008-04-04 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080611115745/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/04/this_week_in_chiefs_history6/ |archivedate = June 11, 2008}}</ref> DeBerg spent four seasons with the Chiefs, leading the team to 2 postseason appearances (in [[1990 Kansas City Chiefs season|1990]], he did so despite playing with a broken finger).<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\"/> DeBerg compiled 11,873 passing yards, 67 touchdowns and 50 interceptions with the Chiefs with an 81.8 [[passer rating]].<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\"/><ref name=\"DeBerg\">{{cite web | title=Steve DeBerg | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DebeSt00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> DeBerg's best year was 1990 with a 101.2 quarterback rating, passing for 3,444 yards, 23 touchdowns and only 4 interceptions.\n\n[[Image:Joe Montana ESPN cropped2.jpg|thumb|left|In his first season with the team, Joe Montana led the Chiefs to their first [[AFC Championship]] Game appearance, a feat they would not accomplish again until [[2018 NFL season|2018]].]]\nOn April 21, 1993, Kansas City acquired quarterback [[Joe Montana]], safety [[David Whitmore]], and a third-round draft pick in the [[1993 NFL Draft]] ([[Will Shields]]) by sending their first-round selection to the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref name=\"Chiefs and 49ers\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs and 49ers come to terms on Montana trade at last | last=Friend | first=Tom | work=New York Times | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE3DE1331F932A15757C0A965958260&scp=7&sq=joe%20montana%20Chiefs&st=cse | date=1993-04-21 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Montana had already agreed on a three-year, $10 million contract before getting traded.<ref name=\"Chiefs and 49ers\"/> Montana would lead the Chiefs to the [[AFC Championship Game]], a feat they would not accomplish again until [[2018 NFL season|2018]]. He was also selected to the [[1994 Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> In 1994, Montana led the Chiefs into [[Mile High Stadium]] to face [[John Elway]] and the [[Denver Broncos]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/10/19/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history20/ | date=2007-10-19 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023174701/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/10/19/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history20/ |archivedate = October 23, 2007}}</ref> Elway performed some of his late-game magic but it was Montana who stole the show in a game later known as the \"Monday Night Shootout.\"<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> The two teams entered the fourth quarter tied at 21, and a Chiefs field goal put the team on top 24&ndash;21.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> After a turnover by the Broncos, Kansas City appeared ready to run out the clock behind [[running back]] [[Marcus Allen]].<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> Allen fumbled, leaving the Broncos with possession of the ball, and Elway led the Broncos to a touchdown to give Denver a 28&ndash;24 lead.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> However, with 1:29 remaining, Montana led the Chiefs 75 yards down the field to score the last minute go ahead touchdown, and the Chiefs snapped an 11-game losing streak to Denver with a 31&ndash;28 victory.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/>\n\n[[Image:061231Jaguars-Chiefs.jpg|right|thumb|Trent Green lines up with the Chiefs' offense, 2006.]]\nAfter the departure of Elvis Grbac in 2001, the Chiefs acquired Trent Green in a trade with the St. Louis Rams. In his first season, Green struggled and was called \"a big disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web | date=2007-01-03 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070126051815/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/03/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_ii/ |archivedate = January 26, 2007|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/03/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_ii/ | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part II | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website }}</ref> Phil Kloster famously nicknamed him \"Tr-INT\" after he had a particularly rough outing versus Denver in which he threw 4 interceptions to Deltha O'Neal. This was later picked up from Chiefs fan page Chiefsplanet by Jason Whitlock who printed the moniker in the Kansas City Star and took the nickname to fame.<ref name=\"What's up III\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part III | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/04/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_iii/\n | date=2007-01-04 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070213162514/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/04/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_iii/ |archivedate = February 13, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"What's up IV\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part IV | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/05/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_iv/ | date=2007-01-05 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070212153701/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/05/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_iv/ |archivedate = February 12, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"What's up V\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part V | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/06/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_v/ | date=2007-01-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080317200754/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/06/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_v/ |archivedate = March 17, 2008}}</ref> By his third season, Green led the Chiefs to a 13&ndash;3 record in 2003 and was called the \"mastermind of the Chiefs' high-powered offense.\"<ref name=\"What's up III\"/> In 2004, Green threw for 4,591&nbsp;yards and a league-high 556 passing attempts.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeTr00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Green was selected to two [[Pro Bowl]] games in 2003 and 2005.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/><ref name=\"Green\"/> Green's 81-game start streak for the Chiefs from 2001&ndash;2006 is a franchise record at the position.<ref name=\"Green to Rams\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green agrees to three-year deal to return to Rams | agency=Associated Press | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/rams/2008-03-10-green-return_N.htm | date=2008-03-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> His 88 career starts for the Chiefs is second behind Dawson.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> Green is the Chiefs' career leader in [[passer rating]] (87.3),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> average gain per attempt (7.7),<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Green to Rams\"/> 300-yard passing games (24),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> completion percentage (61.94),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> and completions of 20 or more yards (274).<ref name=\"Green to Rams\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs agree to trade QB Trent Green to Miami | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www2.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/06/chiefs_agree_to_trade_qb_trent_green_to_miami/ | date=2007-06-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711001202/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/06/chiefs_agree_to_trade_qb_trent_green_to_miami/ | archivedate=2007-07-11 }}</ref> He is the only quarterback in Chiefs history to throw a [[List of NFL quarterbacks who have posted a perfect passer rating|\"perfect game\"]] registering a 158.3 [[passer rating]] against [[Detroit Lions|Detroit]] on December 14, 2003.<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n\nIn the past few decades, the Chiefs have relied on veteran quarterbacks to lead their team.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/><ref name=\"Quarterback\">{{cite web | title=The quarterback myth | last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ | date=2006-04-27 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203315/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007 }}</ref> The Chiefs never drafted their own quarterback to develop until [[Brodie Croyle]] was chosen in the [[2006 NFL Draft]] and claimed the starting position in [[2007 Kansas City Chiefs season|2007]].<ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> In the years prior to drafting Croyle (1960&ndash;2005), the Chiefs had drafted 30 quarterbacks and each led the team to victory just 57 times, or 15%.<ref name=\"Quarterback\"/>\n\nWhen head coach [[Herman Edwards]] was hired in [[2006 Kansas City Chiefs season|2006]], he stated that he was looking towards implementing a \"youth movement\" into his game plan, and he began his roster moves at the quarterback position.<ref name=\"Several '08\">{{cite web | title=Several '08 picks should make immediate impact | last=Williamson | first=Bill | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=williamson_bill&id=3448409 | date=2008-06-18 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> Croyle was the team's starting quarterback heading into the 2008 season, however, he suffered an injury and [[Damon Huard]] played in Croyle's absence.<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/><ref name=\"Several '08\"/> Huard started the Chiefs' game in Week 2,<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/> but he himself suffered an injury and [[Tyler Thigpen]] substituted for the remainder of the game.<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs' Huard replaced by Thigpen after injury | agency=Associated Press| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3587431 | date=2008-09-14| accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref> Thigpen started for the Chiefs in Huard and Croyle's absence against the Falcons.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs QB Thigpen to start vs. Falcons | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861 | date=2008-09-17 | accessdate=2008-09-17}}</ref> Croyle returned in Week 7 to start against the [[Tennessee Titans]] but suffered a season-ending knee injury.<ref name=\"Croyle sprains\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chiefs QB Croyle sprains right knee, done for the season  | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3652130 | date=2008-10-19 | accessdate=2008-10-19}}</ref> Following the injuries to Croyle and Huard, Thigpen became the ''[[de facto]]'' starting quarterback.<ref name=\"ThigpenPFR\">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/ThigTy00.htm | accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Spread changes\">{{cite web | title=Spread changes options for Chiefs | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?id=3717080 | last=Chadiha | first=Jeffri | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-11-21 | accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref>\n\nAfter a poor first career start for Thigpen against Atlanta, a game in which he threw three interceptions, the Chiefs implemented the [[spread offense]].<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> With the absence of RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]], the central part of the Chiefs' offense in years past, offensive coordinator [[Chan Gailey]] adjusted the offense to mimic the spread formation run by Thigpen at [[Coastal Carolina University|Coastal Carolina]].<ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\">{{cite web|title=Breaking the Mold |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ |last=Rand |first=Jonathan |work=Kansas City Chiefs official website |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2008-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110191420/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ |archivedate=January 10, 2009 }}</ref> It was considered by many in the NFL as a gamble, since there have been doubts over the spread offense's longterm success at the professional level.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> It was also a new direction for head coach [[Herman Edwards]], who has long had a reputation for favoring more conservative, run-oriented offenses.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> After it was implemented, Edwards began seeing his team gain confidence with every game it played in that wide-open system, as the Chiefs began to become competitive once again on offense.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/>\n\n[[File:TylerThigpen110908.jpg|left|thumb|Tyler Thigpen avoids a sack from [[Shaun Phillips]], 2008.]]\nThe switch to the spread offense paid off for Thigpen and his abilities.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/><ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\"/> Prior to the Chiefs implementing the spread offense, Thigpen had been playing erratically with the Chiefs, and he suddenly became poised and effective running the new offense.<ref name=\"A copycat game\">{{cite web|title=A copycat game |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ |last=Rand |first=Jonathan |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2008-12-02 |accessdate=2008-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206125042/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref> In Thigpen's second career start, he passed for 280 yards with a 69.4% completion rate, with two touchdowns and no interceptions against the [[New York Jets]], nearly leading the Chiefs to win over the heavily favored Jets.<ref name=\"Favre connects\">{{cite web | title=Favre connects with Coles in final minute to lift Jets to win | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281026020 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-10-26 | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> Thigpen's passer rating climbed from 44.3 to 76.9 in the five games following his initial start at Atlanta.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/> The Chiefs scored more than 10 points just twice in their first six games, but scored more offensive points than that in every game since, and twice topped 25 points.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/>\n\nThigpen won his first game as the Chiefs' starter on November 30 against the Oakland Raiders, leading Kansas City to a 20&ndash;13 victory.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\">{{cite web | title=Johnson's 2-yard plunge lifts Chiefs over woeful Raiders | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281130013 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-11-30 | accessdate=2008-12-01}}</ref> Thigpen finished 15-for-22 for 162 yards and ran for 48 more.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The offensive gameplan finally paid off and resulted in a victory which ended a 7-game losing streak for the Chiefs.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/><ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> Thigpen ended the season starting nine games for Chiefs with a 1&ndash;8 record. Six of the losses were within 7-point or less margins. He registered 21 total touchdowns, 12 interceptions, and 2,994 all-purpose yards.<ref name=\"Thigpen\">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/ThigTy00.htm | accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2009, the Chiefs acquired QB [[Matt Cassel]] and LB [[Mike Vrabel]] from the [[New England Patriots]] for the #34 overall selection in the [[2009 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Chiefs complete\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs complete trade for Cassel | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/28/chiefs.trade.for.cassel/index.html | last=King | first=Peter | work=Sports Illustrated | date=2009-02-28 | accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Cassel, Vrabel\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs acquire QB Matt Cassel, LB Mike Vrabel in trade with Patriots |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-02-28 |accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304002108/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots |archivedate=March 4, 2009 }}</ref> Cassel competed with Thigpen for the starting quarterback position during training camp and won decisively.<ref name=\"Q&A Haley March 2, 2009\">{{cite web|title=Q&A with head coach Todd Haley |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/02/qa_with_todd_haley_3_2_09/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306121610/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/02/qa_with_todd_haley_3_2_09 |archivedate=March 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nMatt Cassel did not have immediate success as the starter for Kansas City, as he led the team to a 4\u201312 season in 2009, throwing for 2,924 yards and 16 touchdowns, while also throwing 16 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/8644/matt-cassel|website=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> The next year as the starter, he showed marked improvement, and helped the Chiefs attain a 10\u20136 record in 2010 by throwing for 3,116 yards, 27 touchdowns, and only 7 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CassMa00.htm|website=pro-football-reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC.|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> Cassel's effective quarterback play helped the Kansas City Chiefs win the AFC West and return to the postseason, where they faced the Baltimore Ravens.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moseman|first1=Doc|title=2010 NFL Playoffs: Baltimore Ravens at Kansas City Chiefs Predictions and Odds|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/566684-2010-nfl-playoffs-ravens-at-chiefs-predictions-and-odds|website=Bleacher Report|publisher=Bleacher Report, Inc.|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> The game ended with a loss, however, with the final score being 30\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 NFL Playoffs Wildcard Weekend: Road Rules|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/playoffs/2010/matchup/_/teams/ravens-chiefs|website=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> Cassel began the 2011 season as the starting quarterback, however during a loss in Week 10 against the Denver Broncos, he injured his hand and did not play the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web| title = Chiefs QB Matt Cassel placed on injured reserve with hand injury, ending his season. | work = Washington Post/Associated Press | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/chiefs-qb-matt-cassel-placed-on-injured-reserve-with-hand-injury-ending-his-season/2011/11/21/gIQA1oBDjN_story.html | date = 2011-11-21 | accessdate = 2011-11-22}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Tyler Palko]], who had only thrown six passes in his career up to that point. He started four games for Chiefs, and led them to a 1\u20133 record before being benched in a 37\u201310 loss to the Jets in Week 14. [[Kyle Orton]], the former Denver Broncos quarterback, was chosen to start the Week 15 game against the formerly unbeaten 13-0 Green Bay Packers, and led them to an improbable upset. The next game, Orton led the Chiefs to a close loss in overtime against the Oakland Raiders, ending their hopes of a playoff bid. They finished the season at 7\u20139, with nine games started by Cassel, four by Palko, and three by Orton.<ref>http://www.nfl.com/schedules/2011/REG/CHIEFS</ref> The Chiefs began their 2012 season with high hopes, but they were quickly dashed, as both Cassel and late season replacement [[Brady Quinn]], also a former Broncos quarterback, split the 2012 season even with 8 games started each. The team tied with the [[2012 Arizona Cardinals season|2012 Arizona Cardinals]] for most interceptions (20) with Cassel throwing 12 and Quinn throwing 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/statistics/player/_/stat/passing/sort/interceptions |title=2012 NFL Player Passing Stats \u2013 National Football League \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=December 31, 2012}}</ref> The Chiefs ended with the worst record in the NFL in offensive passing<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/team/_/name/kc/kansas-city-chiefs |title=Kansas City Chiefs Football Clubhouse \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=December 31, 2012}}</ref> and finished the season with a 2\u201314 record. Subsequently, head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] and general manager [[Scott Pioli]] were both fired, and the Chiefs brought in former Eagles head coach [[Andy Reid]] and [[John Dorsey (American football)|John Dorsey]] to be head coach and general manager.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2012.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2013, a trade made by Dorsey brought in former No. 1 overall pick [[Alex Smith]]. Around the same time, the Chiefs also released Matt Cassel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel released by Kansas City Chiefs|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000150655/article/matt-cassel-released-by-kansas-city-chiefs|work=NFL.com}}</ref> Alex Smith took the former 2-14 team and led them to a 9\u20130 start and an 11\u20135 record, as a strong defense and a decent offense led them to a playoff berth. Alex Smith also recorded 3,313 yards, twenty-three touchdowns, and only seven interceptions. However, the Chiefs were stunned as they lost in the Wildcard Round to the fourth seeded Indianapolis Colts 45-44 after leading by 38-10 early in the 3rd quarter.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2013.htm</ref>\n\nThe next season, the Chiefs put up a second straight winning season under the new Andy Reid/Alex Smith system, however their 9\u20137 record was not enough to make the playoffs.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2014.htm</ref> Alex Smith again finished with a similar season, putting up 3,265 yards, eighteen touchdowns, and six interceptions.<ref>http://www.nfl.com/player/alexsmith/2506340/profile</ref> In the following season, the Chiefs started with a 1\u20135 record, however improved quarterback play and defense led the Chiefs on an improbable 11-game winning streak, culminating with the team's first playoff win since 1993, where they beat the [[Houston Texans]] by a score of 30\u20130. The Chiefs, however, fell short of an [[AFC Championship Game]] bid as the Chiefs lost to the defending Super Bowl champion New England Patriots.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2015.htm</ref>  Alex Smith recorded his career high in passing yards that season, however, with 3,486 yards, and also had twenty touchdowns and seven interceptions. In 2016, Alex Smith started his fourth straight season as Chiefs quarterback. He was injured in Week 8 against the Indianapolis Colts, however he only missed one game and backup quarterback [[Nick Foles]] led them to a 19\u201314 win over the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] the following week. In Week 12, Alex Smith also led the Chiefs to a 30\u201327 overtime win against the defending Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, and put the Chiefs at 8\u20133 on the season.\n\nIn 2017, the Chiefs drafted [[Patrick Mahomes]]<ref>http://www.nfl.com/draft/2017/tracker#dt-tabs:dt-by-team/dt-by-team-input:kc</ref> with the 10th selection in the draft. Mahomes spent almost all of that season as the backup to Smith, and on December 31, 2017, with the Chiefs' playoff seeding already secured and most of the starters resting until the following week's Wild Card Round matchup with the [[Tennessee Titans]],  Mahomes made his NFL debut as the starting QB, leading the Chiefs to a 27\u201324 victory over the [[Denver Broncos]]. The Chiefs traded Alex Smith to the Washington Redskins after the season and named Mahomes as the starting QB for 2018. Mahomes quickly showed off his talents on the field, setting an NFL record with 10 TD passes in his first 3 games <ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/chiefs/2018/09/23/chiefs-patrick-mahomes-record-touchdown-passes-three-weeks/1404587002/</ref> and throwing for 300 yards in 8 of the first 9 games of the 2018 season. Mahomes ultimately finished the 2018 season with 5,097 passing yards and 50 touchdowns, becoming the youngest player since [[Dan Marino]] in 1984 to throw for that many yards, and the second player in NFL history, along with [[Peyton Manning]], to throw for 5,000 passing yards and 50 touchdowns in the same season. For his performance, he was named the [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]], and he also received several other awards and accolades.\n\n=== Backup quarterbacks ===\n[[Image:Halo3LaunchInSeattle WarrenMoon.jpg|thumb|right|After Rich Gannon's departure, Warren Moon served as Elvis Grbac's backup.<ref name=\"Relearning\"/> Moon started one game for Kansas City in the 2000 season.<ref name=\"Moon\"/>]]\nNotable backup quarterbacks have also led the Chiefs to success after substituting for their starting quarterback, including [[Mike Livingston]],<ref name=\"Livingston\">{{cite web | title=Mike Livingston | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/L/LiviMi00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> [[Rich Gannon]],<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite web | title=Rich Gannon | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GannRi00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> and [[Damon Huard]].<ref name=\"Huard\">{{cite web | title=Damon Huard | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HuarDa00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> When [[Len Dawson]] was injured during the Chiefs\u2019 1969 season, second-year quarterback [[Mike Livingston]] won all six of his starts in Dawson's absence.<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/> Dawson returned late in the season to lead the Chiefs on way to [[Super Bowl IV]].<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/> Livingston, surrounded by a much weaker cast when he got another chance to start, never enjoyed much success again.<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/><ref name=\"1969 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=1969 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1969.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> [[Tom Flores]] was also on the Chiefs' 1969 team that won [[Super Bowl IV]], but never played in a game for the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Flores\">{{cite web | title=Tom Flores | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlorTo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> He went on to coach the [[Oakland Raiders]] to two [[Super Bowl]] victories in the 1980s. [[Warren Moon]] was on the Chiefs' roster for the 1999 and 2000 seasons under Elvis Grbac and started one game in Grbac's absence.<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite web | title=Warren Moon | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MoonWa00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"2000 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=2000 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2000.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs saw Moon\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs saw best and last of Moon | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ | date=2006-02-07 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060209034806/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ |archivedate = February 9, 2006 }}</ref><ref name=\"November 26, 2000\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Chiefs at San Diego Chargers \u2013 November 26, 2000 | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200011260sdg.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Moon was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2006.<ref name=\"Moon\"/> [[Ron Jaworski]] finished his career as a Chief in 1989, and started three games.<ref name=\"Jaworski\">{{cite web | title=Ron Jaworski | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JawoRo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Quarterback controversies ===\n\n==== Gannon and Grbac ====\nA [[Glossary of American football#Q|quarterback controversy]] began in the [[1997 Kansas City Chiefs season|1997 season]] when [[Elvis Grbac]] started the first nine games and suffered an injury, leading to [[Rich Gannon]]'s substitution for the next six games.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/> Grbac would return in the team's season finale.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/> Gannon won five consecutive starts down the stretch to help the Chiefs earn home-field advantage with a 13&ndash;3 record.<ref name=\"Gannon, Johnson\">{{cite web | title=Gannon, Johnson take long climbs to Super Bowl summitt | last=Bell | first=Jarrett | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/super/2003-01-23-bonus-gannon-johnson_x.htm | date=2003-01-23 | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> Grbac wasn't much of a leader, in fact he once made the comment \"I can't catch the ball and throw it, too.\"<ref name=\"Thinking\"/><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> although he was a talented thrower.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Gannon was an aggressive leader who demanded the most of his players.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Grbac was selected by coach [[Marty Schottenheimer]] to start the team's playoff game against the [[Denver Broncos]], a game which the Chiefs would lose 14&ndash;10.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Gannon, Johnson\"/> Chiefs fans were deeply divided over whether Gannon or Grbac should lead the team, and Gannon backers were none too happy when he was let go and signed with the Raiders in 1999.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Relearning\">{{cite web | title=Relearning a rivalry| last=Rand | first=Jonathan | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/07/24/relearning_a_rivalry/ | date=2008-07-24 | accessdate=2008-07-27 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080802142858/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/07/24/relearning_a_rivalry/ |archivedate = August 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter joining the Raiders, Gannon knocked the Chiefs out of playoff contention in the 1999 season when the Raiders defeated the Chiefs by a score of 41&ndash;38 in overtime.<ref name=\"Relearning\"/><ref name=\"January 2, 2000\">{{cite web | title=Oakland Raiders at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 2nd, 2000 | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200001020kan.htm | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> Grbac was released by the Chiefs after the [[2000 Kansas City Chiefs season|2000 season]] and signed with the then-[[Super Bowl XXXV|defending Super Bowl champion]] [[Baltimore Ravens]]. Grbac only lasted one season in Baltimore and retired in the offseason. In 2002, Gannon would be named [[NFL Most Valuable Player Award|the NFL's Most Valuable Player]] and led the Raiders to an appearance in [[Super Bowl XXXVII]].<ref name=\"Relearning\"/>\n\n==== Quarterback instability under Herman Edwards (2006&ndash;2008) ====\n[[Image:Huard and Croyle.JPG|thumb|300px|right|[[Damon Huard]] (left) and [[Brodie Croyle]] (right) at a Chiefs mini camp practice.]]\n\nTrent Green had proven himself incredibly durable in his tenure with the Chiefs, and had started every game for the Chiefs since they acquired him in a 2001 trade.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> Green suffered a severe concussion in the 2006 season opener, when he was hit outside the pocket by [[Cincinnati Bengals]] defensive end [[Robert Geathers]].<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> The injury would sideline him for the next eight games.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/><ref name=\"Green to undergo\">{{cite web | title=Green to undergo further tests after suffering grade-three concussion | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3054843 | date=2007-10-08 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> He considered retirement but said [[neurosurgeon]]s and [[neurophysiologist]]s told him he faced no increased risk of [[Alzheimer's disease]] or [[dementia]] if he resumed playing with the team.<ref name=\"Green to undergo\"/> [[Damon Huard]] took over in Green's absence while Green recovered, and coach [[Herman Edwards]] stated that Green would reclaim the position when he got healthy.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=Huard lifts Chiefs into playoff hunt | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=2650819 | date=2006-11-06 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> The situation with Huard was compared to the Gannon&ndash;Grbac controversy from seven years earlier.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Until he replaced Green in week one, Huard had thrown one pass in a game since 2000 and started in six games.<ref name=\"Huard performing\">{{cite web | title=Huard performing a tough act to follow| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/10/26/rand_huard_performing_a_tough_act_to_follow/ | date=2006-10-26 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200938/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/10/26/rand_huard_performing_a_tough_act_to_follow/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Huard played in ten games throwing 11 touchdown passes and only one interception for a quarterback rating of 98.0 with the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Huard\"/> The Chiefs went 5&ndash;3 in games with Huard starting, but when [[Trent Green]] reclaimed his starting job, he managed a 4&ndash;4 record and threw 7 touchdowns and 9 interceptions. When Green returned, the opinions of Chiefs fans were divided.<ref name=\"outside\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green is on outside looking in | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2879180 | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> Half wanted Damon Huard while others remained loyal to Green.<ref name=\"outside\"/> Edwards eventually chose Green to start the team's playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]].<ref name=\"outside\"/> Edwards had said that if Green struggled, he wouldn't hesitate to substitute Huard into the game:<ref name=\"Herm Edwards to Trent Green\">{{cite web | title=Herm Edwards to Trent Green: I Love Ya, But I Just Bought a Hook | last=Yoon | first=Phil | url=http://nfl.fanhouse.com/2007/01/03/herm-edwards-to-trent-green-i-love-ya-but-i-just-bought-a-hoo/ | date=2007-01-03 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|You have to win the game...There's no tomorrow. And you have to do whatever is best for the football team at that point. I'll do whatever I have to do. When you're in the playoffs, you're desperate.<ref name=\"Herm Edwards to Trent Green\"/>}}\n\nThe Chiefs' offense stumbled in the 23&ndash;8 loss,<ref name=\"outside\"/> and Green threw for 107&nbsp;yards on 14-of-24 passing with two interceptions.<ref name=\"Colts turn up the 'D'\">{{cite web | title=Colts turn up the 'D' in 23-8 wild-card win | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29182&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2006&week=POST18 | date=2007-01-06 | accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref> Kansas City's initial first down came with 3:34 remaining in the third quarter, and managed 126 total yards on offense.<ref name=\"Colts turn up the 'D'\"/>\n\nIn late January, Chiefs [[general manager]] [[Carl Peterson]] told Green that he would have to restructure his contract to remain with the team and to brace for a lesser role on offense.<ref name=\"outside\"/> Green was also granted permission to explore options of a trade.<ref name=\"Joint statement\">{{cite web | title=Joint statement from Carl Peterson and Jim Steiner | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2007/03/06/joint_statement_from_chiefs_president_carl_peterson_and_jim_steiner/ | date=2006-03-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161436/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2007/03/06/joint_statement_from_chiefs_president_carl_peterson_and_jim_steiner/ |archivedate = October 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\"/> The February 2007 contract agreement with Huard, who would have been an unrestricted free agent, was the first public indication that Green's job was in danger.<ref name=\"chopped\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chief to be chopped? | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2790000 | date=2006-03-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The first team to have contacted the Chiefs' front office about acquiring Green was the [[Miami Dolphins]], but Miami disagreements prolonged trade talks.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\">{{cite web | last=Pasquarelli | first=Len | title=Dolphins expected to pursue trade for Chiefs' Green | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2838254 | date=2007-04-15 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The Dolphins initially offered a seventh round draft pick to the Chiefs, but the Chiefs declined, instead seeking a second round pick in exchange for Green.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> The [[Detroit Lions]] and [[Cleveland Browns]] were also interested in Green, whom were both looking for a veteran quarterback.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> Green had told the Chiefs that Miami was his preference for a trade,<ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\"/> being that he previously worked under both head coach [[Cam Cameron]] and longtime quarterbacks coach [[Terry Shea]].<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/><ref name=\"outside\"/> On draft day, the Chiefs and Dolphins could not reach a trade agreement. Green voiced his frustration,<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/><ref name=\"QB situation\"/> and criticism was drawn to the Chiefs' apparent neglect to trade Green.<ref name=\"QB situation\">{{cite web | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | title=QB situation not a distraction for Edwards | work=ESPN| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203315/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nGreen stated that he was being treated unfairly on and off the field and that the 2007 quarterback competition was \"substantially weighted\" towards [[Brodie Croyle]], who was drafted in 2006.<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\">{{cite web | last=Lerner | first=Keven | title=Trent Green saga continues | work=South Florida Sun Sentinel | url=http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/sports_football_dolphins/2007/05/trent_green_sag.html | date=2007-05-07 | accessdate=2008-07-29 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009130838/http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/sports_football_dolphins/2007/05/trent_green_sag.html | archivedate=2007-10-09 }}</ref> Green voiced his reluctance to be a backup to Croyle and Huard.<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/> [[Head coach]] [[Herman Edwards]] voiced his own displeasure with Green's outspoken comments and simply said that he was \"trying to create competition.\" The changes had become apparent to Green, whom learned of the dismissal of quarterbacks coach [[Terry Shea]] from Croyle.<ref name=\"outside\"/> He had also pointed out numerous occasions where Edwards had expressed the intention to start a younger quarterback to go along with the others in the [[AFC West]].<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/> Green's agent had also said that the Dolphins were willing to be \"flexible\" in the trade negotiations, but the Chiefs organization were reportedly ignoring their calls in late May.<ref name=\"Green's agent\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Green's agent says Chiefs won't return calls | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2882010 | date=2007-05-24 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nOn June 5, the Chiefs agreed to trade Green to the Miami Dolphins for a conditional fifth round pick in the [[2008 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/><ref name=\"GreenDolphins\">{{cite web | last=Pasquarelli | first=Len | title=Green goes to Dolphins | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2894600 | date=2007-06-05 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The pick could have been upgraded to a fourth-round selection if Green reached certain predetermined playing time and performance levels.<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/><ref name=\"GreenDolphins\"/> A season-ending concussion sent Green to the disabled list, securing a fifth-round choice for the Chiefs.\n\n[[Image:Tyler Thigpen.JPG|thumb|upright|Tyler Thigpen was the third Chiefs quarterback to start a game in 2008.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\"/>]]\nOn August 25, Huard was named the Chiefs' starting quarterback for the season opener against the [[Houston Texans]].<ref name=\"Backup no more\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Backup no more: Huard earns starting role in K.C. | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp07/news/story?id=2991036 | date=2007-08-25 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> However, following an unproductive first half of the season Croyle was named the starter on November 12.<ref name=\"Huard out\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Huard out, Croyle in as Chiefs' starting quarterback | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3107200 | date=2007-11-12 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Huard was injured in a game the previous day against the Denver Broncos, and Croyle filled in for the remainder of the game. Croyle started his first NFL regular season game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]] at the [[RCA Dome]] on November 18, 2007, but the Chiefs lost the game 13&ndash;10.<ref name=\"Huard out\"/><ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Vinatieri's field goal with 4 ticks left wins it for Colts | work=ESPN| url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=271118011 | date=2007-11-18 | accessdate=2008-07-31}}</ref> The Chiefs finished the season losing 9 consecutive games (a club record) and ended with a 4&ndash;12 record, their worst in 30 years. Croyle started six of the last seven games for the Chiefs, losing all six.\n\nIn 2008, Croyle started the Chiefs' opening game against the [[New England Patriots]], but suffered a shoulder injury.<ref name=\"Croyle out\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chiefs QB Croyle out for this week| work=ESPN| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true | date=2008-09-08 | accessdate=2008-09-12}}</ref> Huard played for the remainder of the game and started the team's Week 2 matchup against the [[Oakland Raiders]].<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/> Huard was injured in the game and replaced by [[Tyler Thigpen]].<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\"/> Thigpen was the third Chiefs starting quarterback in the 2008 season.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\"/> The Chiefs prepared Croyle throughout their bye week in order to return in Week 7 against the [[Tennessee Titans]]. Croyle suffered a season-ending knee injury in the game, and when Huard substituted, he suffered a thumb injury leading to Thigpen finishing the game at quarterback.<ref name=\"Croyle sprains\"/> After the game, it was confirmed that both Croyle and Huard were placed on injured reserve, and Thigpen was announced as the starter against the Jets in Week 8.<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\">{{cite web | title=Johnson will not play for second straight week; Thigpen to start at QB | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3658139 | agency=Associated Press | work=ESPN | date=2008-10-23 | accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> The Chiefs signed both [[Ingle Martin]] and [[Quinn Gray]] to replace both Croyle and Huard on the depth chart.<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\"/><ref name=\"Ingle Martin\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City signs QB Ingle Martin and WR Marques Hagans |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/09/10/kansas_city_signs_qb_ingle_martin_and_wr_marques_hagans/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2008-09-10 |accessdate=2009-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013140043/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/09/10/kansas_city_signs_qb_ingle_martin_and_wr_marques_hagans/ |archivedate=October 13, 2008 }}</ref> Thigpen started the remaining ten games of the season, but the Chiefs finished with a franchise-worst 2&ndash;14 record and continued to lack stability at the QB position under head coach Herman Edwards.\n\n== Franchise records ==\nThe following is a list of franchise records accomplished by Texans/Chiefs quarterbacks from 1960&ndash;2018.\n\n=== Career ===\n*'''Games started, total:''' Len Dawson, 158 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/>\n*'''Games played, total:''' Len Dawson, 182 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/>\n*'''Games started, consecutive:''' Trent Green, 81 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Passing yards:''' Len Dawson, 28,507 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Touchdown passes:''' Len Dawson, 237 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Most passes had intercepted:''' Len Dawson, 178 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"Dawson\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most consecutive games, touchdowns passes:''' Elvis Grbac, 15 (November 28, 1999 to November 12, 2000).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Highest passer rating:''' Trent Green, 87.3 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green returns to Rams\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green agrees to 3-year deal to return to Rams | agency=Associated Press | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/rams/2008-03-10-green-return_N.htm | date=2008-03-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Passing attempts:''' Len Dawson, 3,696 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Passing completions:''' Len Dawson, 2,115 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Passing completion percentage:''' Trent Green, 61.94 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Most 300-yard passing games:''' Trent Green, 24 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Regular season wins:''' Len Dawson, 94 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Times sacked (compiled since 1972):''' Bill Kenney, 195 (1980&ndash;1988).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\">{{cite web | author=Kansas City Chiefs | title=Kansas City Chiefs Franchise Records (1960&ndash;2005) | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/media/misc/2006_records.pdf | year=2006 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529222014/http://www.kcchiefs.com/media/misc/2006_records.pdf |archivedate = May 29, 2008}}</ref>\n*'''Longest pass completion:''' Trent Green to [[Marc Boerigter]], 99 (December 12, 2002 vs. San Diego Chargers).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Lowest percentage, passes had intercepted:''' Elvis Grbac, 3.04 (1,548-47) (1997\u20132000).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n=== Season ===\n*'''Touchdown passes:''' Patrick Mahomes, 50 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Touchdown passes, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 6 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained:''', Patrick Mahomes, 5,097 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 1,484 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes had intercepted:''' Trent Green, 24 (2001).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes had intercepted, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 14 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Fumbles:''' Steve Fuller, 16 (1980).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Times sacked (compiled since 1972):''' Steve Fuller, 49 (1980).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passing attempts:''' Bill Kenney, 603 (1983).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passing completions:''' Patrick Mahomes, 369 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most 300-yard passing games:''' Patrick Mahomes, 10 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passing attempts, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 270 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passing completions, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 146 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n=== Game ===\n*'''First quarterback to throw and catch a touchdown pass:''' Tyler Thigpen (November 2, 2008 vs. Tampa Bay Buccaneers).<ref name=\"Bucs overcome\">{{cite web | title=Bucs overcome four turnovers, 21-point deficit en route to OT win | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281102012 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2008-11-02 | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref>\n*'''Youngest quarterback to start:''' Patrick Mahomes (December 31, 2018 vs. Denver Broncos).<ref name=\"November 18, 2007\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs vs Broncos \u2013 December 31, 2017| work=ESPN official website | url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400951789 | date=2017-12-31 | accessdate=2018-11-04 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215032552/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/12/chiefs_vs_colts__game_10a07/ |archivedate = December 15, 2007}}</ref>\n*'''Oldest quarterback to start:''' Warren Moon, 44 (November 26, 2000 vs. San Diego Chargers).<ref name=\"Chiefs saw best\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs saw best and last of Moon | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ | date=2006-02-07 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060209034806/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ |archivedate = February 9, 2006}}</ref>\n*'''Touchdown passes:'''Two players tied&ndash;'' Len Dawson; Patrick Mahomes, 6 (November 1, 1964 vs. Denver Broncos; September 16, 2018 vs. Pittsburgh Steelers).<ref name=\"This Week, November 2, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ | date=2007-11-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204195508/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ |archivedate = December 4, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Highest passer rating:''' Trent Green, 158.3 (December 12, 2002 vs. Detroit Lions).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes attempted:''' ''Two players tied&ndash;''Joe Montana; Steve Bono, 55 (October 9, 1994 vs. San Diego Chargers; December 12, 1994 vs. Miami Dolphins).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes attempted, no interceptions:''' Trent Green, 47 (December 7, 2003 vs. Denver Broncos).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes completed:''' Elvis Grbac, 39 (November 5, 2000 vs. Oakland Raiders).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes completed, consecutive:''' Len Dawson, 16 (September 9, 1967 vs. Houston Oilers).<ref name=\"This Week, November 2, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained:''' Elvis Grbac, 504 (November 5, 2000 vs. Oakland Raiders).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Times sacked:''' Steve Fuller, 10 (November 2, 1980 vs. Baltimore Colts).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passes had intercepted:''' Todd Blackledge, 6 (October 20, 1985 vs. Los Angeles Rams).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterbacks]]\n*[[List of Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n;General\n* Althaus, Bill (2007). ''The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly: Kansas City Chiefs: Heart-Pounding, Jaw-Dropping, and Gut-Wrenching Moments in Kansas City Chiefs History'', Triumph Books. {{ISBN|1-57243-928-9}}\n* Herb, Patrick, Kuhbander, Brad, Looney, Josh, and Moris, Pete, eds. ''2008 Kansas City Chiefs Media Guide'', Kansas City Chiefs Football Club, Inc., 2008\n;Specific\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Kansas City Chiefs}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterback navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|a complete list of starting quarterbacks by season|List of Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterbacks}}\n[[File:Alex Smith 2014 Pro Bowl.jpg|thumb|upright|Former Chiefs quarterback Alex Smith at the 2014 Pro Bowl]]\n31 [[quarterbacks]] have started for the [[National Football League]]'s [[Kansas City Chiefs]] since their franchise began. The team has also had numerous backup quarterbacks that have stolen the spotlight from the starters.<ref name=\"Thinking\">{{cite web | title=Thinking about quarterbacks| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2003/09/12/thinking_about_quarterbacks | date=2003-09-12 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203515/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2003/09/12/thinking_about_quarterbacks |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Controversy\">{{cite web | title=Quarterbacks and controversy| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/11/01/gretz_quarterbacks__controversy/ | date=2006-11-01 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200842/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/11/01/gretz_quarterbacks__controversy/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nUnder [[Len Dawson]], the Texans/Chiefs won three [[American Football League]] championships and appeared in two [[Super Bowl]] championship games. Dawson was named [[Super Bowl MVP|Most Valuable Player]] following the Chiefs' victory in [[Super Bowl IV]]. Dawson played a total of 13 seasons with Kansas City and retired with many franchise records. Despite having little success in developing and drafting a quality quarterback of their own, the Chiefs have achieved success under many veteran quarterbacks, including [[Dave Krieg]], [[Joe Montana]], [[Elvis Grbac]], [[Trent Green]] and [[Alex Smith]]. The Chiefs have often relied on veteran leadership at the position.<ref name=\"Althaus 167\">Althaus, p. 167</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs' next hope\">{{cite web | title=Cassel is Chiefs' next hope | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3954904 | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2009-03-06 | accessdate=2009-03-06}}</ref> It wasn't until 2017 the Chiefs were able to successfully draft and groom a quarterback of their own, [[Patrick_Mahomes|Patrick Mahomes]], who brought them their first [[AFC_Championship_Game|AFC Championship]] title and second Super Bowl victory.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Starting quarterbacks ===\nThe Chiefs have had many notable and established quarterbacks on their squad at different times. Hall of Famers [[Len Dawson]] and [[Joe Montana]] led the Chiefs in two successful eras and both led the team to playoff appearances in their first seasons.<ref name=\"1962 Texans\">{{cite web | title=1962 Dallas Texans season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1962.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"1993 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=1993 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1993.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise's first starter was [[Cotton Davidson]], who started 25 games for the Texans before being traded in 1962.<ref name=\"Davidson\">{{cite web | title=Cotton Davidson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DaviCo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Team owner [[Lamar Hunt]] traded Davidson to the [[Oakland Raiders]] for the first-overall selection in the [[American Football League Draft|1963 AFL Draft]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/07/06/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history7/ | archive-url=https://archive.is/20070502213724/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/07/06/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history7/ | url-status=dead | archive-date=2007-05-02 | date=2007-07-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The franchise used that pick to select future Hall of Fame [[defensive tackle]] [[Buck Buchanan]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/>\n\nIn Davidson's absence, free agent quarterback [[Len Dawson]] signed with the team on July 2, 1962 after spending a five-year career in the NFL with [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh]] and [[Cleveland Browns|Cleveland]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> In Dallas, Dawson was rejoined with head coach [[Hank Stram]] who served as an assistant coach with [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]], where Dawson played college football.<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> In his first season with the Texans, Dawson led the team to a double-overtime victory over the [[Houston Oilers]] in the [[American Football League playoffs|AFL Championship Game]].<ref name=\"This Week, July 6, 2007\"/> The victory brought the team's first league championship.\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  =\"'Lenny the Cool'...He was our leader. He was the man.\"<ref name=\"Althaus 6\"/>\n | source = \u2014 [[Buck Buchanan]], Chiefs defensive end (1963&ndash;1975).\n | width  =33%\n | align  =right\n}}\n\nLen Dawson was the franchise's most successful quarterback, playing in 182 regular season games (158 starts) for the Texans/Chiefs, and holds many franchise records.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/08/10/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history12/ | date=2007-08-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070502213724/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/08/10/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history12/ | archivedate=2007-05-02 }}</ref> He was nicknamed \"Lenny the Cool\" for his calm composure on the field.<ref name=\"Althaus 6\">Althaus, p. 6</ref><ref name=\"Althaus 1\">Althaus, p. 1</ref> Dawson completed 2,115 of 3,696 passes for 28,507&nbsp;yards with 237 touchdowns and 178 interceptions, good for an 82.6 career rating. He ranks first in team history in pass attempts, completions, passing yards and touchdowns.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> He led the Chiefs to 94 regular season wins and three AFL titles.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson led the Chiefs to an appearance in [[Super Bowl I|the first AFL&ndash;NFL Championship Game]] (later known as \"Super Bowl I\") against the [[Green Bay Packers]].<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> He was named [[Super Bowl MVP|MVP]] of [[Super Bowl IV]] when he directed Kansas City to a 23&ndash;7 victory over the [[Minnesota Vikings]].<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson was named to six AFL All-Star teams and one [[Pro Bowl]] squad, in addition to being named the AFL Player of the Year in 1962.<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/> Dawson was also named the [[Walter Payton Man of the Year|NFL Man of the Year]] in [[1973 NFL season|1973]].<ref name=\"Dawson\">{{cite web | title=Len Dawson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DawsLe00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Dawson threw a franchise record six touchdown passes against the [[Denver Broncos]] on November 1, 1964 in a 49&ndash;39 victory.<ref name=\"This Week, Nov 2, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ | date=2007-11-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204195508/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ |archivedate = December 4, 2007 }}</ref> In 1966, while still playing for the Chiefs, Dawson became the sports director and anchor for [[KMBC-TV]], a local Kansas City [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate.<ref name=\"Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV\">{{cite web | title=Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV News Team Story | url=http://www.kmbc.com/kmbcnewsteam/276477/detail.html | publisher=KMBC.com | accessdate=2009-02-15 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202063010/http://www.kmbc.com/kmbcnewsteam/276477/detail.html | archivedate=2008-12-02 }}</ref> As of 2009, Dawson is still KMBC's sports director.<ref name=\"Len Dawson \u2013 KMBC-TV\"/> He would practice and play for the Chiefs during the day and later help anchor news broadcasts at night.<ref name=\"Althaus 3\"/> After retiring from the NFL in 1975,<ref name=\"Great ones\">{{cite web|title=Great ones hard to find |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/04/great_ones_hard_to_find/ |last=Gretz |first=Bob |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-03-04 |accessdate=2009-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309132730/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/04/great_ones_hard_to_find |archivedate=March 9, 2009 }}</ref> Dawson began hosting ''[[Inside the NFL]]'' on HBO and worked network broadcasts for [[NBC]].<ref name=\"Althaus 3\">Althaus, p. 3</ref> He joined the Chiefs' radio broadcast team in 1984 and provides color commentary to game broadcasts.<ref name=\"Althaus 3\"/>\n\n[[Bill Kenney]] was the team's starting quarterback in various times between 1980 and 1988 and compiled a 46&ndash;51 record.<ref name=\"Althaus 166\">Althaus, p. 166</ref> Kenney played behind a porous offensive line and holds the franchise record for most times [[quarterback sack|sacked]] (195).<ref name=\"Althaus 166\"/> Kenney's All-Pro wide receiver teammate [[Carlos Carson]] said, \"I don't care who you are, it's tough to throw a pass when you're lying on your back.\"<ref name=\"Althaus 166\"/> Kenney was selected to the [[1984 Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> After retiring from professional football, Kenney became a [[State Senator]] for the [[Missouri Senate]].\n\nThe Chiefs made a mistake in drafting quarterback [[Todd Blackledge]] in the [[1983 NFL Draft]] believing that Blackledge was a better choice than [[Jim Kelly]] and [[Dan Marino]].<ref name=\"Althaus 167\"/><ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> Blackledge never started a full season for Kansas City while Kelly and Marino played Hall of Fame careers.<ref name=\"Warrick\">{{cite web | title=Warrick, Klinger fell way short in Cincy | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft08/news/story?id=3326109 | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2008-04-16 | accessdate=2009-01-16}}</ref> Blackledge started 24 total games in Kansas City, but inconsistent play led to him sharing time with [[Bill Kenney]] from 1984&ndash;1987.<ref name=\"Warrick\"/><ref name=\"Blackledge\">{{cite web | title=Todd Blackledge | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BlacTo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1987 season, the Chiefs used five starting quarterbacks for the only time in franchise history.<ref name=\"History 80s\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Chiefs History&ndash;1980's | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/ | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501122552/http://www.kcchiefs.com/history/80s/ |archivedate = May 1, 2008}}</ref> Doug Hudson was the last quarterback drafted by the team to start a game until [[Brodie Croyle]] started in 2007.<ref name=\"Huard out\"/> In Hudson's only game, he was [[Quarterback sack|sacked]] in the endzone for a [[Safety (American football score)|safety]] by the [[Denver Broncos]]' [[Jim Ryan (American football)|Jim Ryan]].<ref name=\"October 18, 1987\">{{cite web | title=Denver Broncos at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 October 18, 1987 | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/198710180kan.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The sack and fumble is the only recorded statistic for his career.<ref name=\"Hudson\">{{cite web | title=Doug Hudson | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HudsDo20.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the Chiefs traded two draft selections and [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] [[Mark Robinson (American football)|Mark Robinson]] to the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in exchange for veteran quarterback [[Steve DeBerg]].<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/04/this_week_in_chiefs_history6/ | date=2008-04-04 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080611115745/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/04/04/this_week_in_chiefs_history6/ |archivedate = June 11, 2008}}</ref> DeBerg spent four seasons with the Chiefs, leading the team to 2 postseason appearances (in [[1990 Kansas City Chiefs season|1990]], he did so despite playing with a broken finger).<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\"/> DeBerg compiled 11,873 passing yards, 67 touchdowns and 50 interceptions with the Chiefs with an 81.8 [[passer rating]].<ref name=\"This Week, April 4, 2008\"/><ref name=\"DeBerg\">{{cite web | title=Steve DeBerg | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DebeSt00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> DeBerg's best year was 1990 with a 101.2 quarterback rating, passing for 3,444 yards, 23 touchdowns and only 4 interceptions.\n\n[[Image:Joe Montana ESPN cropped2.jpg|thumb|left|In his first season with the team, Joe Montana led the Chiefs to their first [[AFC Championship]] Game appearance, a feat they would not accomplish again until [[2018 NFL season|2018]].]]\nOn April 21, 1993, Kansas City acquired quarterback [[Joe Montana]], safety [[David Whitmore]], and a third-round draft pick in the [[1993 NFL Draft]] ([[Will Shields]]) by sending their first-round selection to the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref name=\"Chiefs and 49ers\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs and 49ers come to terms on Montana trade at last | last=Friend | first=Tom | work=New York Times | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE3DE1331F932A15757C0A965958260&scp=7&sq=joe%20montana%20Chiefs&st=cse | date=1993-04-21 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Montana had already agreed on a three-year, $10 million contract before getting traded.<ref name=\"Chiefs and 49ers\"/> Montana would lead the Chiefs to the [[AFC Championship Game]], a feat they would not accomplish again until [[2018 NFL season|2018]]. He was also selected to the [[1994 Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> In 1994, Montana led the Chiefs into [[Mile High Stadium]] to face [[John Elway]] and the [[Denver Broncos]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/10/19/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history20/ | date=2007-10-19 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023174701/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/10/19/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history20/ |archivedate = October 23, 2007}}</ref> Elway performed some of his late-game magic but it was Montana who stole the show in a game later known as the \"Monday Night Shootout.\"<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> The two teams entered the fourth quarter tied at 21, and a Chiefs field goal put the team on top 24&ndash;21.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> After a turnover by the Broncos, Kansas City appeared ready to run out the clock behind [[running back]] [[Marcus Allen]].<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> Allen fumbled, leaving the Broncos with possession of the ball, and Elway led the Broncos to a touchdown to give Denver a 28&ndash;24 lead.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/> However, with 1:29 remaining, Montana led the Chiefs 75 yards down the field to score the last minute go ahead touchdown, and the Chiefs snapped an 11-game losing streak to Denver with a 31&ndash;28 victory.<ref name=\"This Week, October 19, 2007\"/>\n\n[[Image:061231Jaguars-Chiefs.jpg|right|thumb|Trent Green lines up with the Chiefs' offense, 2006.]]\nAfter the departure of Elvis Grbac in 2001, the Chiefs acquired Trent Green in a trade with the St. Louis Rams. In his first season, Green struggled and was called \"a big disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web | date=2007-01-03 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070126051815/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/03/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_ii/ |archivedate = January 26, 2007|url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/03/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_ii/ | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part II | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website }}</ref> Phil Kloster famously nicknamed him \"Tr-INT\" after he had a particularly rough outing versus Denver in which he threw 4 interceptions to Deltha O'Neal. This was later picked up from Chiefs fan page Chiefsplanet by Jason Whitlock who printed the moniker in the Kansas City Star and took the nickname to fame.<ref name=\"What's up III\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part III | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/04/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_iii/\n | date=2007-01-04 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070213162514/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/04/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb__part_iii/ |archivedate = February 13, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"What's up IV\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part IV | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/05/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_iv/ | date=2007-01-05 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070212153701/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/05/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_iv/ |archivedate = February 12, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"What's up V\">{{cite web | title=What's up with coverage of KC's QB? Part V | last=Dawes | first=Rufus | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/06/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_v/ | date=2007-01-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080317200754/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/01/06/dawes_whats_up_with_coverage_of_kcs_qb_part_v/ |archivedate = March 17, 2008}}</ref> By his third season, Green led the Chiefs to a 13&ndash;3 record in 2003 and was called the \"mastermind of the Chiefs' high-powered offense.\"<ref name=\"What's up III\"/> In 2004, Green threw for 4,591&nbsp;yards and a league-high 556 passing attempts.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeTr00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Green was selected to two [[Pro Bowl]] games in 2003 and 2005.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/><ref name=\"Green\"/> Green's 81-game start streak for the Chiefs from 2001&ndash;2006 is a franchise record at the position.<ref name=\"Green to Rams\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green agrees to three-year deal to return to Rams | agency=Associated Press | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/rams/2008-03-10-green-return_N.htm | date=2008-03-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> His 88 career starts for the Chiefs is second behind Dawson.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/> Green is the Chiefs' career leader in [[passer rating]] (87.3),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> average gain per attempt (7.7),<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Green to Rams\"/> 300-yard passing games (24),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> completion percentage (61.94),<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/> and completions of 20 or more yards (274).<ref name=\"Green to Rams\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs agree to trade QB Trent Green to Miami | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www2.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/06/chiefs_agree_to_trade_qb_trent_green_to_miami/ | date=2007-06-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711001202/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/06/06/chiefs_agree_to_trade_qb_trent_green_to_miami/ | archivedate=2007-07-11 }}</ref> He is the only quarterback in Chiefs history to throw a [[List of NFL quarterbacks who have posted a perfect passer rating|\"perfect game\"]] registering a 158.3 [[passer rating]] against [[Detroit Lions|Detroit]] on December 14, 2003.<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n\nIn the past few decades, the Chiefs have relied on veteran quarterbacks to lead their team.<ref name=\"Great ones\"/><ref name=\"Quarterback\">{{cite web | title=The quarterback myth | last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ | date=2006-04-27 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203315/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007 }}</ref> The Chiefs never drafted their own quarterback to develop until [[Brodie Croyle]] was chosen in the [[2006 NFL Draft]] and claimed the starting position in [[2007 Kansas City Chiefs season|2007]].<ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> In the years prior to drafting Croyle (1960&ndash;2005), the Chiefs had drafted 30 quarterbacks and each led the team to victory just 57 times, or 15%.<ref name=\"Quarterback\"/>\n\nWhen head coach [[Herman Edwards]] was hired in [[2006 Kansas City Chiefs season|2006]], he stated that he was looking towards implementing a \"youth movement\" into his game plan, and he began his roster moves at the quarterback position.<ref name=\"Several '08\">{{cite web | title=Several '08 picks should make immediate impact | last=Williamson | first=Bill | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=williamson_bill&id=3448409 | date=2008-06-18 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarterback\"/> Croyle was the team's starting quarterback heading into the 2008 season, however, he suffered an injury and [[Damon Huard]] played in Croyle's absence.<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/><ref name=\"Several '08\"/> Huard started the Chiefs' game in Week 2,<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/> but he himself suffered an injury and [[Tyler Thigpen]] substituted for the remainder of the game.<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs' Huard replaced by Thigpen after injury | agency=Associated Press| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3587431 | date=2008-09-14| accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref> Thigpen started for the Chiefs in Huard and Croyle's absence against the Falcons.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs QB Thigpen to start vs. Falcons | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3593861 | date=2008-09-17 | accessdate=2008-09-17}}</ref> Croyle returned in Week 7 to start against the [[Tennessee Titans]] but suffered a season-ending knee injury.<ref name=\"Croyle sprains\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chiefs QB Croyle sprains right knee, done for the season  | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3652130 | date=2008-10-19 | accessdate=2008-10-19}}</ref> Following the injuries to Croyle and Huard, Thigpen became the ''[[de facto]]'' starting quarterback.<ref name=\"ThigpenPFR\">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/ThigTy00.htm | accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Spread changes\">{{cite web | title=Spread changes options for Chiefs | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?id=3717080 | last=Chadiha | first=Jeffri | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-11-21 | accessdate=2008-11-26}}</ref>\n\nAfter a poor first career start for Thigpen against Atlanta, a game in which he threw three interceptions, the Chiefs implemented the [[spread offense]].<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> With the absence of RB [[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]], the central part of the Chiefs' offense in years past, offensive coordinator [[Chan Gailey]] adjusted the offense to mimic the spread formation run by Thigpen at [[Coastal Carolina University|Coastal Carolina]].<ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\">{{cite web|title=Breaking the Mold |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ |last=Rand |first=Jonathan |work=Kansas City Chiefs official website |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2008-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110191420/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/11/13/breaking_the_mold/ |archivedate=January 10, 2009 }}</ref> It was considered by many in the NFL as a gamble, since there have been doubts over the spread offense's longterm success at the professional level.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> It was also a new direction for head coach [[Herman Edwards]], who has long had a reputation for favoring more conservative, run-oriented offenses.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/> After it was implemented, Edwards began seeing his team gain confidence with every game it played in that wide-open system, as the Chiefs began to become competitive once again on offense.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/>\n\n[[File:TylerThigpen110908.jpg|left|thumb|Tyler Thigpen avoids a sack from [[Shaun Phillips]], 2008.]]\nThe switch to the spread offense paid off for Thigpen and his abilities.<ref name=\"Spread changes\"/><ref name=\"Breaking the Mold\"/> Prior to the Chiefs implementing the spread offense, Thigpen had been playing erratically with the Chiefs, and he suddenly became poised and effective running the new offense.<ref name=\"A copycat game\">{{cite web|title=A copycat game |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ |last=Rand |first=Jonathan |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2008-12-02 |accessdate=2008-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206125042/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/12/02/a_copycat_game/ |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref> In Thigpen's second career start, he passed for 280 yards with a 69.4% completion rate, with two touchdowns and no interceptions against the [[New York Jets]], nearly leading the Chiefs to win over the heavily favored Jets.<ref name=\"Favre connects\">{{cite web | title=Favre connects with Coles in final minute to lift Jets to win | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281026020 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-10-26 | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref> Thigpen's passer rating climbed from 44.3 to 76.9 in the five games following his initial start at Atlanta.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/> The Chiefs scored more than 10 points just twice in their first six games, but scored more offensive points than that in every game since, and twice topped 25 points.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/>\n\nThigpen won his first game as the Chiefs' starter on November 30 against the Oakland Raiders, leading Kansas City to a 20&ndash;13 victory.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\">{{cite web | title=Johnson's 2-yard plunge lifts Chiefs over woeful Raiders | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281130013 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN | date=2008-11-30 | accessdate=2008-12-01}}</ref> Thigpen finished 15-for-22 for 162 yards and ran for 48 more.<ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> The offensive gameplan finally paid off and resulted in a victory which ended a 7-game losing streak for the Chiefs.<ref name=\"A copycat game\"/><ref name=\"Johnson's 2-yard\"/> Thigpen ended the season starting nine games for Chiefs with a 1&ndash;8 record. Six of the losses were within 7-point or less margins. He registered 21 total touchdowns, 12 interceptions, and 2,994 all-purpose yards.<ref name=\"Thigpen\">{{cite web | title=Tyler Thigpen | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/T/ThigTy00.htm | accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2009, the Chiefs acquired QB [[Matt Cassel]] and LB [[Mike Vrabel]] from the [[New England Patriots]] for the #34 overall selection in the [[2009 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Chiefs complete\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs complete trade for Cassel | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/02/28/chiefs.trade.for.cassel/index.html | last=King | first=Peter | work=Sports Illustrated | date=2009-02-28 | accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref><ref name=\"Cassel, Vrabel\">{{cite web|title=Chiefs acquire QB Matt Cassel, LB Mike Vrabel in trade with Patriots |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-02-28 |accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304002108/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/02/28/chiefs_acquire_qb_matt_cassel_lb_mike_vrabel_in_trade_with_patriots |archivedate=March 4, 2009 }}</ref> Cassel competed with Thigpen for the starting quarterback position during training camp and won decisively.<ref name=\"Q&A Haley March 2, 2009\">{{cite web|title=Q&A with head coach Todd Haley |url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/02/qa_with_todd_haley_3_2_09/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306121610/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2009/03/02/qa_with_todd_haley_3_2_09 |archivedate=March 6, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nMatt Cassel did not have immediate success as the starter for Kansas City, as he led the team to a 4-12 season in 2009, throwing for 2,924 yards and 16 touchdowns, while also throwing 16 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/8644/matt-cassel|website=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> The next year as the starter, he showed marked improvement, and helped the Chiefs attain a 10-6 record in 2010 by throwing for 3,116 yards, 27 touchdowns, and only 7 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CassMa00.htm|website=pro-football-reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC.|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> Cassel's effective quarterback play helped the Kansas City Chiefs win the AFC West and return to the postseason, where they faced the Baltimore Ravens.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Moseman|first1=Doc|title=2010 NFL Playoffs: Baltimore Ravens at Kansas City Chiefs Predictions and Odds|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/566684-2010-nfl-playoffs-ravens-at-chiefs-predictions-and-odds|website=Bleacher Report|publisher=Bleacher Report, Inc.|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> The game ended with a loss, however, with the final score being 30-7.<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 NFL Playoffs Wildcard Weekend: Road Rules|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/playoffs/2010/matchup/_/teams/ravens-chiefs|website=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=6/4/2014}}</ref> Cassel began the 2011 season as the starting quarterback, however during a loss in Week 10 against the Denver Broncos, he injured his hand and did not play the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web| title = Chiefs QB Matt Cassel placed on injured reserve with hand injury, ending his season. | work = Washington Post/Associated Press | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/chiefs-qb-matt-cassel-placed-on-injured-reserve-with-hand-injury-ending-his-season/2011/11/21/gIQA1oBDjN_story.html | date = 2011-11-21 | accessdate = 2011-11-22}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Tyler Palko]], who had only thrown six passes in his career up to that point. He started four games for Chiefs, and led them to a 1-3 record before being benched in a 37-10 loss to the Jets in Week 14. [[Kyle Orton]], the former Denver Broncos quarterback, was chosen to start the Week 15 game against the formerly unbeaten 13-0 Green Bay Packers, and led them to an improbable upset. The next game, Orton led the Chiefs to a close loss in overtime against the Oakland Raiders, ending their hopes of a playoff bid. They finished the season at 7-9, with nine games started by Cassel, four by Palko, and three by Orton.<ref>http://www.nfl.com/schedules/2011/REG/CHIEFS</ref> The Chiefs began their 2012 season with high hopes, but they were quickly dashed, as both Cassel and late season replacement [[Brady Quinn]], also a former Broncos quarterback, split the 2012 season even with 8 games started each. The team tied with the [[2012 Arizona Cardinals season|2012 Arizona Cardinals]] for most interceptions (20) with Cassel throwing 12 and Quinn throwing 8.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/statistics/player/_/stat/passing/sort/interceptions |title=2012 NFL Player Passing Stats \u2013 National Football League \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=December 31, 2012}}</ref> The Chiefs ended with the worst record in the NFL in offensive passing<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/team/_/name/kc/kansas-city-chiefs |title=Kansas City Chiefs Football Clubhouse \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=December 31, 2012}}</ref> and finished the season with a 2-14 record. Subsequently, head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] and general manager [[Scott Pioli]] were both fired, and the Chiefs brought in former Eagles head coach [[Andy Reid]] and [[John Dorsey (American football)|John Dorsey]] to be head coach and general manager.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2012.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2013, a trade made by Dorsey brought in former No. 1 overall pick [[Alex Smith]]. Around the same time, the Chiefs also released Matt Cassel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Cassel released by Kansas City Chiefs|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000150655/article/matt-cassel-released-by-kansas-city-chiefs|work=NFL.com}}</ref> Alex Smith took the former 2-14 team and led them to a 9-0 start and an 11-5 record, as a strong defense and a decent offense led them to a playoff berth. Alex Smith also recorded 3,313 yards, twenty-three touchdowns, and only seven interceptions. However, the Chiefs were stunned as they lost in the Wildcard Round to the fourth seeded Indianapolis Colts 45-44 after leading by 38-10 early in the 3rd quarter.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2013.htm</ref>\n\nThe next season, the Chiefs put up a second straight winning season under the new Andy Reid/Alex Smith system, however their 9-7 record was not enough to make the playoffs.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2014.htm</ref> Alex Smith again finished with a similar season, putting up 3,265 yards, eighteen touchdowns, and six interceptions.<ref>http://www.nfl.com/player/alexsmith/2506340/profile</ref> In the following season, the Chiefs started with a 1-5 record, however improved quarterback play and defense led the Chiefs on an improbable 11-game winning streak, culminating with the team's first playoff win since 1993, where they beat the [[Houston Texans]] by a score of 30-0. The Chiefs, however, fell short of an [[AFC Championship Game]] bid as the Chiefs lost to the defending Super Bowl champion New England Patriots.<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2015.htm</ref>  Alex Smith recorded his career high in passing yards that season, however, with 3,486 yards, and also had twenty touchdowns and seven interceptions. In 2016, Alex Smith started his fourth straight season as Chiefs quarterback. He was injured in Week 8 against the Indianapolis Colts, however he only missed one game and backup quarterback [[Nick Foles]] led them to a 19-14 win over the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] the following week. In Week 12, Alex Smith also led the Chiefs to a 30-27 overtime win against the defending Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, and put the Chiefs at 8-3 on the season.\n\nIn 2017, the Chiefs drafted [[Patrick Mahomes]]<ref>http://www.nfl.com/draft/2017/tracker#dt-tabs:dt-by-team/dt-by-team-input:kc</ref> with the 10th selection in the draft. Mahomes spent almost all of that season as the backup to Smith, and on December 31, 2017, with the Chiefs' playoff seeding already secured and most of the starters resting until the following week's Wild Card Round matchup with the [[Tennessee Titans]],  Mahomes made his NFL debut as the starting QB, leading the Chiefs to a 27-24 victory over the [[Denver Broncos]]. The Chiefs traded Alex Smith to the Washington Redskins after the season and named Mahomes as the starting QB for 2018. Mahomes quickly showed off his talents on the field, setting an NFL record with 10 TD passes in his first 3 games <ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/chiefs/2018/09/23/chiefs-patrick-mahomes-record-touchdown-passes-three-weeks/1404587002/</ref> and throwing for 300 yards in 8 of the first 9 games of the 2018 season. Mahomes ultimately finished the 2018 season with 5,097 passing yards and 50 touchdowns, becoming the youngest player since [[Dan Marino]] in 1984 to throw for that many yards, and the second player in NFL history, along with [[Peyton Manning]], to throw for 5,000 passing yards and 50 touchdowns in the same season. For his performance, he was named the [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]], and he also received several other awards and accolades.\n\n=== Backup quarterbacks ===\n[[Image:Halo3LaunchInSeattle WarrenMoon.jpg|thumb|right|After Rich Gannon's departure, Warren Moon served as Elvis Grbac's backup.<ref name=\"Relearning\"/> Moon started one game for Kansas City in the 2000 season.<ref name=\"Moon\"/>]]\nNotable backup quarterbacks have also led the Chiefs to success after substituting for their starting quarterback, including [[Mike Livingston]],<ref name=\"Livingston\">{{cite web | title=Mike Livingston | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/L/LiviMi00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> [[Rich Gannon]],<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite web | title=Rich Gannon | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GannRi00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> and [[Damon Huard]].<ref name=\"Huard\">{{cite web | title=Damon Huard | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HuarDa00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> When [[Len Dawson]] was injured during the Chiefs\u2019 1969 season, second-year quarterback [[Mike Livingston]] won all six of his starts in Dawson's absence.<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/> Dawson returned late in the season to lead the Chiefs on way to [[Super Bowl IV]].<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/> Livingston, surrounded by a much weaker cast when he got another chance to start, never enjoyed much success again.<ref name=\"Huard performing\"/><ref name=\"1969 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=1969 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/1969.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> [[Tom Flores]] was also on the Chiefs' 1969 team that won [[Super Bowl IV]], but never played in a game for the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Flores\">{{cite web | title=Tom Flores | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/F/FlorTo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> He went on to coach the [[Oakland Raiders]] to two [[Super Bowl]] victories in the 1980s. [[Warren Moon]] was on the Chiefs' roster for the 1999 and 2000 seasons under Elvis Grbac and started one game in Grbac's absence.<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite web | title=Warren Moon | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MoonWa00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"2000 Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=2000 Kansas City Chiefs season| work=Pro Football Reference| url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/kan/2000.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs saw Moon\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs saw best and last of Moon | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ | date=2006-02-07 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060209034806/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ |archivedate = February 9, 2006 }}</ref><ref name=\"November 26, 2000\">{{cite web | title=Kansas City Chiefs at San Diego Chargers \u2013 November 26, 2000 | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200011260sdg.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Moon was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2006.<ref name=\"Moon\"/> [[Ron Jaworski]] finished his career as a Chief in 1989, and started three games.<ref name=\"Jaworski\">{{cite web | title=Ron Jaworski | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/J/JawoRo00.htm | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Quarterback controversies ===\n\n==== Gannon and Grbac ====\nA [[Glossary of American football#Q|quarterback controversy]] began in the [[1997 Kansas City Chiefs season|1997 season]] when [[Elvis Grbac]] started the first nine games and suffered an injury, leading to [[Rich Gannon]]'s substitution for the next six games.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/> Grbac would return in the team's season finale.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/> Gannon won five consecutive starts down the stretch to help the Chiefs earn home-field advantage with a 13&ndash;3 record.<ref name=\"Gannon, Johnson\">{{cite web | title=Gannon, Johnson take long climbs to Super Bowl summitt | last=Bell | first=Jarrett | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/super/2003-01-23-bonus-gannon-johnson_x.htm | date=2003-01-23 | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> Grbac wasn't much of a leader, in fact he once made the comment \"I can't catch the ball and throw it, too.\"<ref name=\"Thinking\"/><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> although he was a talented thrower.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Gannon was an aggressive leader who demanded the most of his players.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Grbac was selected by coach [[Marty Schottenheimer]] to start the team's playoff game against the [[Denver Broncos]], a game which the Chiefs would lose 14&ndash;10.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Gannon, Johnson\"/> Chiefs fans were deeply divided over whether Gannon or Grbac should lead the team, and Gannon backers were none too happy when he was let go and signed with the Raiders in 1999.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Relearning\">{{cite web | title=Relearning a rivalry| last=Rand | first=Jonathan | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2008/07/24/relearning_a_rivalry/ | date=2008-07-24 | accessdate=2008-07-27 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080802142858/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/07/24/relearning_a_rivalry/ |archivedate = August 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter joining the Raiders, Gannon knocked the Chiefs out of playoff contention in the 1999 season when the Raiders defeated the Chiefs by a score of 41&ndash;38 in overtime.<ref name=\"Relearning\"/><ref name=\"January 2, 2000\">{{cite web | title=Oakland Raiders at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 2nd, 2000 | work=Pro Football Reference | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200001020kan.htm | accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> Grbac was released by the Chiefs after the [[2000 Kansas City Chiefs season|2000 season]] and signed with the then-[[Super Bowl XXXV|defending Super Bowl champion]] [[Baltimore Ravens]]. Grbac only lasted one season in Baltimore and retired in the offseason. In 2002, Gannon would be named [[NFL Most Valuable Player Award|the NFL's Most Valuable Player]] and led the Raiders to an appearance in [[Super Bowl XXXVII]].<ref name=\"Relearning\"/>\n\n==== Quarterback instability under Herman Edwards (2006&ndash;2008) ====\n[[Image:Huard and Croyle.JPG|thumb|300px|right|[[Damon Huard]] (left) and [[Brodie Croyle]] (right) at a Chiefs mini camp practice.]]\n\nTrent Green had proven himself incredibly durable in his tenure with the Chiefs, and had started every game for the Chiefs since they acquired him in a 2001 trade.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> Green suffered a severe concussion in the 2006 season opener, when he was hit outside the pocket by [[Cincinnati Bengals]] defensive end [[Robert Geathers]].<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> The injury would sideline him for the next eight games.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/><ref name=\"Green to undergo\">{{cite web | title=Green to undergo further tests after suffering grade-three concussion | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3054843 | date=2007-10-08 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> He considered retirement but said [[neurosurgeon]]s and [[neurophysiologist]]s told him he faced no increased risk of [[Alzheimer's disease]] or [[dementia]] if he resumed playing with the team.<ref name=\"Green to undergo\"/> [[Damon Huard]] took over in Green's absence while Green recovered, and coach [[Herman Edwards]] stated that Green would reclaim the position when he got healthy.<ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\">{{cite web | title=Huard lifts Chiefs into playoff hunt | agency=Associated Press | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=2650819 | date=2006-11-06 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> The situation with Huard was compared to the Gannon&ndash;Grbac controversy from seven years earlier.<ref name=\"Controversy\"/><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Until he replaced Green in week one, Huard had thrown one pass in a game since 2000 and started in six games.<ref name=\"Huard performing\">{{cite web | title=Huard performing a tough act to follow| last=Gretz | first=Bob | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/10/26/rand_huard_performing_a_tough_act_to_follow/ | date=2006-10-26 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200938/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/10/26/rand_huard_performing_a_tough_act_to_follow/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Huard lifts Chiefs\"/> Huard played in ten games throwing 11 touchdown passes and only one interception for a quarterback rating of 98.0 with the Chiefs.<ref name=\"Huard\"/> The Chiefs went 5&ndash;3 in games with Huard starting, but when [[Trent Green]] reclaimed his starting job, he managed a 4&ndash;4 record and threw 7 touchdowns and 9 interceptions. When Green returned, the opinions of Chiefs fans were divided.<ref name=\"outside\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green is on outside looking in | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2879180 | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref> Half wanted Damon Huard while others remained loyal to Green.<ref name=\"outside\"/> Edwards eventually chose Green to start the team's playoff game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]].<ref name=\"outside\"/> Edwards had said that if Green struggled, he wouldn't hesitate to substitute Huard into the game:<ref name=\"Herm Edwards to Trent Green\">{{cite web | title=Herm Edwards to Trent Green: I Love Ya, But I Just Bought a Hook | last=Yoon | first=Phil | url=http://nfl.fanhouse.com/2007/01/03/herm-edwards-to-trent-green-i-love-ya-but-i-just-bought-a-hoo/ | date=2007-01-03 | accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|You have to win the game...There's no tomorrow. And you have to do whatever is best for the football team at that point. I'll do whatever I have to do. When you're in the playoffs, you're desperate.<ref name=\"Herm Edwards to Trent Green\"/>}}\n\nThe Chiefs' offense stumbled in the 23&ndash;8 loss,<ref name=\"outside\"/> and Green threw for 107&nbsp;yards on 14-of-24 passing with two interceptions.<ref name=\"Colts turn up the 'D'\">{{cite web | title=Colts turn up the 'D' in 23-8 wild-card win | url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29182&displayPage=tab_recap&season=2006&week=POST18 | date=2007-01-06 | accessdate=2008-09-14}}</ref> Kansas City's initial first down came with 3:34 remaining in the third quarter, and managed 126 total yards on offense.<ref name=\"Colts turn up the 'D'\"/>\n\nIn late January, Chiefs [[general manager]] [[Carl Peterson]] told Green that he would have to restructure his contract to remain with the team and to brace for a lesser role on offense.<ref name=\"outside\"/> Green was also granted permission to explore options of a trade.<ref name=\"Joint statement\">{{cite web | title=Joint statement from Carl Peterson and Jim Steiner | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://kcchiefs.com/news/2007/03/06/joint_statement_from_chiefs_president_carl_peterson_and_jim_steiner/ | date=2006-03-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161436/http://kcchiefs.com/news/2007/03/06/joint_statement_from_chiefs_president_carl_peterson_and_jim_steiner/ |archivedate = October 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\"/> The February 2007 contract agreement with Huard, who would have been an unrestricted free agent, was the first public indication that Green's job was in danger.<ref name=\"chopped\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chief to be chopped? | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2790000 | date=2006-03-06 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The first team to have contacted the Chiefs' front office about acquiring Green was the [[Miami Dolphins]], but Miami disagreements prolonged trade talks.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\">{{cite web | last=Pasquarelli | first=Len | title=Dolphins expected to pursue trade for Chiefs' Green | work=ESPN | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2838254 | date=2007-04-15 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The Dolphins initially offered a seventh round draft pick to the Chiefs, but the Chiefs declined, instead seeking a second round pick in exchange for Green.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> The [[Detroit Lions]] and [[Cleveland Browns]] were also interested in Green, whom were both looking for a veteran quarterback.<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/> Green had told the Chiefs that Miami was his preference for a trade,<ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\"/> being that he previously worked under both head coach [[Cam Cameron]] and longtime quarterbacks coach [[Terry Shea]].<ref name=\"Dolphins expected\"/><ref name=\"outside\"/> On draft day, the Chiefs and Dolphins could not reach a trade agreement. Green voiced his frustration,<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/><ref name=\"QB situation\"/> and criticism was drawn to the Chiefs' apparent neglect to trade Green.<ref name=\"QB situation\">{{cite web | last=Merrill | first=Elizabeth | title=QB situation not a distraction for Edwards | work=ESPN| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ | date=2007-05-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930203315/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/04/27/gretz_draft_week__the_quarterback_myth/ |archivedate = September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nGreen stated that he was being treated unfairly on and off the field and that the 2007 quarterback competition was \"substantially weighted\" towards [[Brodie Croyle]], who was drafted in 2006.<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\">{{cite web | last=Lerner | first=Keven | title=Trent Green saga continues | work=South Florida Sun Sentinel | url=http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/sports_football_dolphins/2007/05/trent_green_sag.html | date=2007-05-07 | accessdate=2008-07-29 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009130838/http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/sports_football_dolphins/2007/05/trent_green_sag.html | archivedate=2007-10-09 }}</ref> Green voiced his reluctance to be a backup to Croyle and Huard.<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/> [[Head coach]] [[Herman Edwards]] voiced his own displeasure with Green's outspoken comments and simply said that he was \"trying to create competition.\" The changes had become apparent to Green, whom learned of the dismissal of quarterbacks coach [[Terry Shea]] from Croyle.<ref name=\"outside\"/> He had also pointed out numerous occasions where Edwards had expressed the intention to start a younger quarterback to go along with the others in the [[AFC West]].<ref name=\"Trent Green saga\"/> Green's agent had also said that the Dolphins were willing to be \"flexible\" in the trade negotiations, but the Chiefs organization were reportedly ignoring their calls in late May.<ref name=\"Green's agent\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Green's agent says Chiefs won't return calls | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2882010 | date=2007-05-24 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref>\n\nOn June 5, the Chiefs agreed to trade Green to the Miami Dolphins for a conditional fifth round pick in the [[2008 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/><ref name=\"GreenDolphins\">{{cite web | last=Pasquarelli | first=Len | title=Green goes to Dolphins | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2894600 | date=2007-06-05 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> The pick could have been upgraded to a fourth-round selection if Green reached certain predetermined playing time and performance levels.<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/><ref name=\"GreenDolphins\"/> A season-ending concussion sent Green to the disabled list, securing a fifth-round choice for the Chiefs.\n\n[[Image:Tyler Thigpen.JPG|thumb|upright|Tyler Thigpen was the third Chiefs quarterback to start a game in 2008.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\"/>]]\nOn August 25, Huard was named the Chiefs' starting quarterback for the season opener against the [[Houston Texans]].<ref name=\"Backup no more\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Backup no more: Huard earns starting role in K.C. | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp07/news/story?id=2991036 | date=2007-08-25 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> However, following an unproductive first half of the season Croyle was named the starter on November 12.<ref name=\"Huard out\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Huard out, Croyle in as Chiefs' starting quarterback | work=ESPN| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3107200 | date=2007-11-12 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref> Huard was injured in a game the previous day against the Denver Broncos, and Croyle filled in for the remainder of the game. Croyle started his first NFL regular season game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]] at the [[RCA Dome]] on November 18, 2007, but the Chiefs lost the game 13&ndash;10.<ref name=\"Huard out\"/><ref name=\"Green goes to Dolphins\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Vinatieri's field goal with 4 ticks left wins it for Colts | work=ESPN| url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=271118011 | date=2007-11-18 | accessdate=2008-07-31}}</ref> The Chiefs finished the season losing 9 consecutive games (a club record) and ended with a 4&ndash;12 record, their worst in 30 years. Croyle started six of the last seven games for the Chiefs, losing all six.\n\nIn 2008, Croyle started the Chiefs' opening game against the [[New England Patriots]], but suffered a shoulder injury.<ref name=\"Croyle out\">{{cite web | agency=Associated Press | title=Chiefs QB Croyle out for this week| work=ESPN| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80aa747b&template=with-video&confirm=true | date=2008-09-08 | accessdate=2008-09-12}}</ref> Huard played for the remainder of the game and started the team's Week 2 matchup against the [[Oakland Raiders]].<ref name=\"Croyle out\"/> Huard was injured in the game and replaced by [[Tyler Thigpen]].<ref name=\"replaced by Thigpen\"/> Thigpen was the third Chiefs starting quarterback in the 2008 season.<ref name=\"Thigpen to start\"/> The Chiefs prepared Croyle throughout their bye week in order to return in Week 7 against the [[Tennessee Titans]]. Croyle suffered a season-ending knee injury in the game, and when Huard substituted, he suffered a thumb injury leading to Thigpen finishing the game at quarterback.<ref name=\"Croyle sprains\"/> After the game, it was confirmed that both Croyle and Huard were placed on injured reserve, and Thigpen was announced as the starter against the Jets in Week 8.<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\">{{cite web | title=Johnson will not play for second straight week; Thigpen to start at QB | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3658139 | agency=Associated Press | work=ESPN | date=2008-10-23 | accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> The Chiefs signed both [[Ingle Martin]] and [[Quinn Gray]] to replace both Croyle and Huard on the depth chart.<ref name=\"Johnson will not play\"/><ref name=\"Ingle Martin\">{{cite web|title=Kansas City signs QB Ingle Martin and WR Marques Hagans |url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/09/10/kansas_city_signs_qb_ingle_martin_and_wr_marques_hagans/ |publisher=Kansas City Chiefs |date=2008-09-10 |accessdate=2009-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013140043/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2008/09/10/kansas_city_signs_qb_ingle_martin_and_wr_marques_hagans/ |archivedate=October 13, 2008 }}</ref> Thigpen started the remaining ten games of the season, but the Chiefs finished with a franchise-worst 2&ndash;14 record and continued to lack stability at the QB position under head coach Herman Edwards.\n\n== Franchise records ==\nThe following is a list of franchise records accomplished by Texans/Chiefs quarterbacks from 1960&ndash;2018.\n\n=== Career ===\n*'''Games started, total:''' Len Dawson, 158 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/>\n*'''Games played, total:''' Len Dawson, 182 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/>\n*'''Games started, consecutive:''' Trent Green, 81 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Passing yards:''' Len Dawson, 28,507 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Touchdown passes:''' Len Dawson, 237 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Most passes had intercepted:''' Len Dawson, 178 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"Dawson\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most consecutive games, touchdowns passes:''' Elvis Grbac, 15 (November 28, 1999 to November 12, 2000).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Highest passer rating:''' Trent Green, 87.3 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green returns to Rams\">{{cite web | title=Trent Green agrees to 3-year deal to return to Rams | agency=Associated Press | work=USA Today | url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/rams/2008-03-10-green-return_N.htm | date=2008-03-10 | accessdate=2008-07-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Passing attempts:''' Len Dawson, 3,696 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Passing completions:''' Len Dawson, 2,115 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Passing completion percentage:''' Trent Green, 61.94 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Most 300-yard passing games:''' Trent Green, 24 (2001&ndash;2006).<ref name=\"Green\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs agree to trade\"/>\n*'''Regular season wins:''' Len Dawson, 94 (1962&ndash;1975).<ref name=\"This Week, August 10, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Dawson\"/>\n*'''Times sacked (compiled since 1972):''' Bill Kenney, 195 (1980&ndash;1988).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\">{{cite web | author=Kansas City Chiefs | title=Kansas City Chiefs Franchise Records (1960&ndash;2005) | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website| url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/media/misc/2006_records.pdf | year=2006 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529222014/http://www.kcchiefs.com/media/misc/2006_records.pdf |archivedate = May 29, 2008}}</ref>\n*'''Longest pass completion:''' Trent Green to [[Marc Boerigter]], 99 (December 12, 2002 vs. San Diego Chargers).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Lowest percentage, passes had intercepted:''' Elvis Grbac, 3.04 (1,548-47) (1997\u20132000).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n=== Season ===\n*'''Touchdown passes:''' Patrick Mahomes, 50 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Touchdown passes, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 6 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained:''', Patrick Mahomes, 5,097 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 1,484 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes had intercepted:''' Trent Green, 24 (2001).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes had intercepted, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 14 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Fumbles:''' Steve Fuller, 16 (1980).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Times sacked (compiled since 1972):''' Steve Fuller, 49 (1980).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passing attempts:''' Bill Kenney, 603 (1983).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passing completions:''' Patrick Mahomes, 369 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most 300-yard passing games:''' Patrick Mahomes, 10 (2018).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passing attempts, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 270 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passing completions, rookie:''' Steve Fuller, 146 (1979).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n=== Game ===\n*'''First quarterback to throw and catch a touchdown pass:''' Tyler Thigpen (November 2, 2008 vs. Tampa Bay Buccaneers).<ref name=\"Bucs overcome\">{{cite web | title=Bucs overcome four turnovers, 21-point deficit en route to OT win | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281102012 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN.com | date=2008-11-02 | accessdate=2008-11-14}}</ref>\n*'''Youngest quarterback to start:''' Patrick Mahomes (December 31, 2018 vs. Denver Broncos).<ref name=\"November 18, 2007\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs vs Broncos \u2013 December 31, 2017| work=ESPN official website | url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400951789 | date=2017-12-31 | accessdate=2018-11-04 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215032552/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/12/chiefs_vs_colts__game_10a07/ |archivedate = December 15, 2007}}</ref>\n*'''Oldest quarterback to start:''' Warren Moon, 44 (November 26, 2000 vs. San Diego Chargers).<ref name=\"Chiefs saw best\">{{cite web | title=Chiefs saw best and last of Moon | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ | date=2006-02-07 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060209034806/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2006/02/07/rand_chiefs_saw_best_and_last_of_moon/ |archivedate = February 9, 2006}}</ref>\n*'''Touchdown passes:'''Two players tied&ndash;'' Len Dawson; Patrick Mahomes, 6 (November 1, 1964 vs. Denver Broncos; September 16, 2018 vs. Pittsburgh Steelers).<ref name=\"This Week, November 2, 2007\">{{cite web | title=This Week in Chiefs History | work=Kansas City Chiefs official website | url=http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ | date=2007-11-02 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204195508/http://www.kcchiefs.com/news/2007/11/02/kuhbander_this_week_in_chiefs_history22/ |archivedate = December 4, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Highest passer rating:''' Trent Green, 158.3 (December 12, 2002 vs. Detroit Lions).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes attempted:''' ''Two players tied&ndash;''Joe Montana; Steve Bono, 55 (October 9, 1994 vs. San Diego Chargers; December 12, 1994 vs. Miami Dolphins).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes attempted, no interceptions:''' Trent Green, 47 (December 7, 2003 vs. Denver Broncos).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes completed:''' Elvis Grbac, 39 (November 5, 2000 vs. Oakland Raiders).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Passes completed, consecutive:''' Len Dawson, 16 (September 9, 1967 vs. Houston Oilers).<ref name=\"This Week, November 2, 2007\"/><ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Yards gained:''' Elvis Grbac, 504 (November 5, 2000 vs. Oakland Raiders).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Times sacked:''' Steve Fuller, 10 (November 2, 1980 vs. Baltimore Colts).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n*'''Most passes had intercepted:''' Todd Blackledge, 6 (October 20, 1985 vs. Los Angeles Rams).<ref name=\"Chiefs Records\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterbacks]]\n*[[List of Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n;General\n* Althaus, Bill (2007). ''The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly: Kansas City Chiefs: Heart-Pounding, Jaw-Dropping, and Gut-Wrenching Moments in Kansas City Chiefs History'', Triumph Books. {{ISBN|1-57243-928-9}}\n* Herb, Patrick, Kuhbander, Brad, Looney, Josh, and Moris, Pete, eds. ''2008 Kansas City Chiefs Media Guide'', Kansas City Chiefs Football Club, Inc., 2008\n;Specific\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Kansas City Chiefs}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs starting quarterback navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStarting quarterbacks:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 4-12 \u2192 4\u201312 (13), 30-7 \u2192 30\u20137 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Kansas_City_Chiefs_quarterbacks"}
{"title_page": "Austin College", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name        = Austin College\n|image       = Austin College logo.svg\n|motto       = ''Nil nisi per aspera''\n|mottoeng    = ''Nothing but the fierce''\n|established = 1849\n|type        = [[Private university|Private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]]\n|affiliation = [[Presbyterian Church USA|Presbyterian]]\n|endowment   = [[United States dollar|$]]133 million<ref>As of November, 2014.  {{cite web | title = Austin College: Adding Value to a Changing World Strategic Plan 2015-2020| publisher = Austin College | url = http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/StrategicPlan-2015-2020.pdf| format = PDF | accessdate = November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n|president   = Steven O'Day\n|students    = 1,223 (2019)<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543 U. S. News]</ref>\n|city        = [[Sherman, Texas|Sherman]]\n|state       = [[Texas]]\n|country     = United States\n|campus      = [[Suburban]], {{convert|70|acre}} \n|free_label  = \n|free        = \n|athletics   = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference|SCAC]] <br/> ''Compete in the [[Southern Athletic Association]] for football''\n|colors      = Crimson & Gold<ref>http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/Brand-Guide-2014.pdf</ref><br/>{{color box|#981E32}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FDB913}}&nbsp;\n|nickname    = Kangaroos, The Fighting 'Roos\n|mascot      = [[Kangaroo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acroos.com/sports/cheer/mascot|title=The Kangaroo Mascot|work=Austin College}}</ref>\n|website= {{url|www.austincollege.edu}}\n|staff       = 104\n|academic_affiliations= [[Oberlin Group]]<br>[[Annapolis Group]]<br>[[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]<br>[[Association of Presbyterian Colleges and Universities|APCU]]\n| logo = \n}}\n\n[[File:AdminAC.JPG|thumb|right|Administrative building]]\n\n'''Austin College''' is a [[private university|private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] affiliated with the [[Presbyterian Church (USA)]] and located in [[Sherman, Texas]].<ref name=\"Austin College History\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/about/history/ Austin College], Austin College History.</ref>\n\nAbout 1,300 students are enrolled at the college.<ref name=\"Austin College Life\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/prospective-students/life-at-austin-college/ Austin College] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611143303/http://www.austincollege.edu/prospective-students/life-at-austin-college/ |date=June 11, 2011 }}, Austin College Life.</ref> Students are required to live on campus for the first three years of their education in order to foster a close-knit and community oriented campus lifestyle. Austin College actively promotes [[study abroad]] programs; 70% of graduates have at least one international study experience during college, and about 82% of students are involved in research.<ref name=\"austincollege.edu1\">http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/ACDifference_Bookmark_2013.pdf</ref> The college cultivates close interaction between students and professors via a 13:1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://premium.usnews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543/rankings|title=Indicator|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> student to faculty ratio and an average class size of fewer than 25 students.<ref name=\"Austin College Faculty\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/academics/faculty/ Austin College], Austin College Faculty.</ref> The college has no teaching assistants, so regular faculty teach all levels of coursework.\n\nChartered in November 1849, Austin College remains the oldest institution of higher education in Texas to be operating under its original charter and name as recognized by the [[Texas Historical Commission|State Historical Survey Committee]].<ref name=\"Austin College History\"/> The college was profiled in all three editions of ''[[Colleges That Change Lives]]''.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Main.GIF|thumb|Old Main]]\nThe college was founded on October 13, 1849, in [[Huntsville, Texas]], by the [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College|Hampden\u2013Sydney]]<ref>{{cite web| title = An Army of Good Men| work = The Record| publisher = Hampden\u2013Sydney College| url = http://www.hsc.edu/The-Record/2010-September/An-army-of-good-men.html| access-date = 2014-04-02| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120111130039/http://www.hsc.edu/The-Record/2010-September/An-army-of-good-men.html| archive-date = 2012-01-11| url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Princeton University|Princeton]]-educated missionary Dr. Daniel Baker. Signed by Texas Governor [[George Tyler Wood|George Wood]], the charter of Austin College was modeled after those of [[Harvard University|Harvard]], [[Yale University|Yale]], and [[Princeton University|Princeton]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = History|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/about/history/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\nBaker named the school for the Texas historical figure [[Stephen F. Austin]] after the original land on which it was built was donated by the Austin family. Two other important figures in Texas history, [[Sam Houston]] and [[Anson Jones]],<ref name=\"Austin College History\" /> served on the original board of trustees for the college, and the former site in Huntsville later became today's [[Sam Houston State University]].\n\nAustin College's founding president was Irish-born Presbyterian minister [[Samuel McKinney]], who served as the school's president a second time from 1862 to 1871.<ref name=\"amelia\">{{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fmc74 |title= MCKINNEY, SAMUEL | first= Amelia W. | last=Williams | date= June 15, 2010| website= Handbook of Texas Online | publisher = [[Texas State Historical Association]] |access-date= September 6, 2015}}</ref> Under the tenure of the fourth president of Austin College, Reverend Samuel Magoffin Luckett,<ref name=\":0\" /> Austin College suffered several [[yellow fever]] epidemics and complications related to [[American Civil War|the Civil War]]. Texas Synod of the Presbyterian Church decided the college would be relocated to Sherman in 1876. Construction of the new campus in north Texas came in the form of \"Old Main,\" a two-story, red brick structure, which occurred between 1876 and 1878. Struggling with the [[Long Depression]]. Austin College saw little improvement to its building or grounds during the late 1870s; as such, Samuel Luckett resigned his position as president. From 1878 to 1885, the college continued to struggle from the aftershocks of economic depression; with an increasing debt and shrinking student body, the college turned to its 7th president, Reverend Donald MacGregor. A shrewd and well connected businessman, President MacGregor relieved a great deal of the college's debt and returned operations to normalcy. After MacGregor's death in 1887, the college welcomed President Luckett back to the campus. Throughout his second term as president, Samuel Luckett adopted a military program, grew the student body, introduced a YMCA chapter, established intercollegiate athletics and Greek fraternities, and added two wings to Old Main.\n\nOne of the school's most iconic presidents came in the form of Reverend Thomas Stone Clyce, who served as the Austin College president from 1900 to 1931; Reverend Clyce's presidency would become, and remains, the longest tenure in Austin College history.\n\nOn January 21 of 1913, Old Main was set ablaze and burnt to the ground in a matter of hours. A professor of Austin College, Davis Foute Eagleton described the incident: {{quote|\"''Austin College on fire and every particle of wood reduced to ashes--and walls rendered totally unfit for use. Oh, dies irae, dies irae! - The dear old building in which I have laboured for twenty-four years, gone! What traditions, memories, griefs, joys, were associated with it! The carpenters were approaching the completion of their work. The new English room was completed, the library room was soon to be ready. The literary societies lost everything. I lost all books, or, [those] in my class room. The laboratories were almost a total loss. Fortunately, the library, records, and office furniture were all in the new Y.M.C.A. building. Before the fire had begun to die out, the Senior class called the student body together and they pledged themselves by classes in writing to stand by the Faculty and the College, and that no one would leave. The Faculty also met shortly after and unanimously decided to continue college work the next day as usual, meeting their classes in places designated. Probably not another institution in the State could have done this.'' ''But the old College building is gone forever!!!\"''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lost Buildings of Austin College 1|url = http://abell.austincollege.edu/visitors/welcome/lost/lostm.html|website = abell.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150908033645/http://abell.austincollege.edu/visitors/welcome/lost/lostm.html|archive-date = 2015-09-08|url-status = dead}}</ref>}}Following the fire, the citizens of Sherman raised $50,000 to help the college rebuild. Now one of the oldest buildings on the Austin College campus, Sherman Hall housed administrative offices, an auditorium-chapel, and a library. Now the home of the [[humanities]] division, Sherman Hall boasted such guests as [[Harry Houdini]], [[Harry Blackstone, Sr.|Harry Blackstone Sr]]., [[Ernestine Schumann-Heink|Madame Schumann-Heink]], [[William Howard Taft]], and [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]].\n\nTo this day, the Austin College administration rarely cancels classes for weather or minor incidents in honor of the great commitment students and faculty made to continue on with regular coursework following the fire.\n\nAustin College became co-educational in 1918, merging in 1930 with the all-female [[Texas Presbyterian College]].\n\n[[Great Depression in the United States|The Great Depression]] severely limited campus growth and educational expansion, however the college quickly regained momentum in the mid-1930s with the introduction of many courses, ground breaking on new facilities, and growth of previously established programs. Throughout 1942, Austin College trained some 300 men and women in engineering, science and management courses as part of the United States Office of Education's war efforts. The following year, Austin College undertook a Cadet nurses training program and hosted Naval Reserves, Texas Home Guard, Army-air trainees and Air Corps Cadets.\n\nOn September 20, 1973, the musician [[Jim Croce]] died in a [[plane crash]] in [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]], on his way to perform the next night at Austin College. Six people died in the crash.\n\nIn 1994, Dr. Oscar Page joined the community as its 14th president. Under his tenure, 1994-2009, Dr. Page increased the school's endowment by nearly 80%, due in large part to his dedicated fundraising efforts as evidenced by the success of the \"Campaign for the New Era;\" a total of $120 million were raised and the campaign was heralded as the largest fundraiser in Austin College's history. Dr. Page orchestrated the construction of Jordan Family Language House, Jerry E. Apple Stadium, the Robert J. and Mary Wright Campus Center, the Robert M. and Joyce A. Johnson 'Roo Suites, and the Betsy Dennis Forster Art Studio Complex; as well as the renovation of  the David E. and Cassie L. Temple Center for Teaching and Learning at Thompson House and of Wortham Center, and creation of the John A. and Katherine G. Jackson Technology Center, the Margaret Binkley Collins and William W. Collins, Jr., Alumni Center, and the College Green in Honor of John D. and Sara Bernice Moseley and Distinguished Faculty.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Past Presidents|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/about/office-of-the-president/past-presidents/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn the latter part of Austin College's history, the school would see de-segregation, welcome its first full-time black faculty member, first female head of a department, and, employ its first female president.\n\nDr. Marjorie Hass joined the campus in 2009 as both its first female and [[Jewish faith]] president. Under her leadership, the college saw the construction of the IDEA Center and two new housing complexes\u2014the Flats at Brockett Court and the Village on Grand. The IDEA Center is a 103,000 square ft. facility which includes multi-disciplinary and multi-purpose classrooms, laboratories, lecture halls and the largest telescope in the region found in Adams Observatory. It is  a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Gold certified facility.<ref>{{Cite web|title = IDEA Center|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/campus-offices/business-affairs/physical-plant/idea/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nOn August 17, 2017 Austin College announced its 16th President, Steven P. O'Day, J.D., former vice president of strategic initiatives at [[Lebanon Valley College]]. O'Day took office on October 30, 2017.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes        = 250\n| USNWR_LA      = 117\n| Wamo_LA       = 116\n}}\nListed in the [[U.S. News & World Report]] \"Guide to the 331 Most Interesting Colleges\", Austin College is ranked #117 on the 2019 list of National Liberal Arts Colleges. Austin College was ranked 79th in 2016. President O'Day took office in 2017, and Austin College slipped to 117th in 2020, the lowest ranking National Liberal Arts College in Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543/rankings?int=c6b9e3| title=Austin College| publisher=U.S. News}}</ref>  The school is named a Best Western College by [[The Princeton Review]] and is also included in The Princeton Review's Best 377 Colleges. Austin College has been ranked as one of the top ten colleges in Texas by [[USA Today]], College Factual, and Best Colleges.\n\nAustin College is a member of the International 50, a group of the top colleges in the US for international focus, the non-profit organization Colleges That Change Lives and is one of the original 40 colleges profiled in the book [[Colleges That Change Lives|Colleges That Change Lives: 40 Schools That Will Change the Way You Feel About Colleges]] by Loren Pope.\n\n==Academics==\nAustin College offers about 35 majors and pre-professional programs for study, and students can also create a specialized major to match their academic interests. The college is known for its nationally recognized five-year Master of Arts in Teaching program, its pre-medical, international studies, and pre-law programs, which draw many students to the campus. The college has a music program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austincollege.edu/music|title=music program|work=austincollege.edu}}</ref> and supports the Austin College A Cappella Choir and the Sherman Symphony Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shermansymphony.com|title=www.shermansymphony.com|work=shermansymphony.com}}</ref> made up of students and local musicians, and assorted smaller musical ensembles. It sponsors the Posey Center of Excellence in Leadership, the Center for Environmental Studies, and the Center for Southwestern and Mexican Studies, three specialized programs that give students numerous research and internship opportunities. The school also has active programs in over 40 academic disciplines. The school's student newspaper, the Austin College ''Observer'', is a bi-weekly publication.\n\n==Athletics==\nAustin College participates in [[NCAA Division III]] athletics. Previously, Austin College competed in NAIA Division II athletics. Austin College athletes do not receive athletic scholarships.  The football team became known as the \"Kangaroos\" sometime during the 1914 to 1915 seasons. According to campus legend, the mascot name was derived from a kangaroo court of organized students that would paddle violators of college rules. Currently students refer to their sports teams as the 'fighting roos.'\n\nKangaroo varsity teams include American football, men and women's soccer, men's and women's cross country, volleyball, men's and women's basketball, swimming and diving, tennis, baseball, softball, and men's and women's water polo. More than 225 student athletics participate in varsity intercollegiate athletics each year. In 2004-2005, 28 students were recognized with all-conference athletic honors and 61 students received all-conference academic honors.\n\nAustin College joined the [[Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference|Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference (SCAC)]] on July 1, 2006, replacing [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]]. Austin College was previously a member of the [[American Southwest Conference]] (ASC), Texas Intercollegiate Athletic Association, and Texas Conference. In 2017, the Austin College football team joined the Southern Athletic Association in football, while remaining a member of the SCAC across all other sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acroos.com/sports/fball/2015-16/releases/20151117uguu1z|title=Austin College Football to Join SAA as Affiliate Member|author=|date=18 November 2015|website=acroos.com}}</ref> The college started fielding varsity men's and women's water polo during the 2018-19 school year; the men participate in the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation (MPSF) while the women compete in [[Collegiate Water Polo Association]] (CWPA) Division III.\n\n=== Baseball ===\nIn 2007, the first year of participating in the SCAC, the Austin College baseball team won the conference tournament, beating Millsaps College 9-7 in the finals. The Roos finished the season with a win-loss record of 22-25. The tournament win was the first ever conference championship for the Roos and the first time the program had ever been in the Regional tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/acmagazine_june07.pdf|title = Austin College Magazine|date = June 2007|access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> [[Carl Iwasaki]] was the head coach for the Roos from 2005 until 2010.  He won two coach of the year awards, the first in 2006 while the Roos were still in the ASC and the second, coming in 2007 after the Roos had joined the SCAC. Coach Iwasaki was replaced by James Rise for the 2011 season who coached for four seasons. Under Rise, the Roos went  11-24 in 2011, 8-29 in 2012, 12-29 in 2013, and 6-33 in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = SCAC|url = http://scacsports.com/information/archives/index2|website = scacsports.com|access-date = 2016-01-22}}</ref> In the fall of 2014, the Roos hired Mike Ramsey, a former TCU baseball player, who in his first year went 8-21.\n\n=== Football ===\nAustin College began its first football season in 1896, making Austin College one of the first teams in the south. Austin College has had 119 straight seasons with a football team. Since its beginning Austin college has won eight conference championships, and one national championship. It has also hosted over 130 all Americans. Currently the football team is coached by Loren Dawson and is currently a member of [[NCAA Division III]] Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference (SCAC). As noted above, the football team moved to the Southern Athletic Association (SAA) in 2017.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Ryan Allen]], opera singer\n* [[Marshall Applewhite]], leader of the Heaven's Gate religious cult.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news| date=1997-03-29| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D07E5DC133AF93AA15750C0A961958260| publisher=New York Times| title=From Religious Childhood To Reins of a U.F.O. Cult| accessdate=2008-05-08 | first=Jacques | last=Steinberg}}</ref>\n* [[Gene Babb]], President, National Football Scouting Inc.; former player for the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Houston Oilers]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n* [[Thomas Henry Ball]], Texas politician and member of the [[United States House of Representatives]]\n* [[Smith Ballew]], actor and singer\n* [[Billy Bookout]], American football player\n* [[Hannibal Boone]], 16th Attorney General of Texas\n* [[Byron Boston]], a football official in the [[National Football League]]\n* [[Joe Coomer (American football)|Joe Coomer]], American football player\n* [[Deborah Crombie]], New York Times bestselling author.\n* [[Philip N. Diehl|Philip Diehl]], Director of the [[United States Mint]]. \n* [[Nancy J. Duff|Nancy Duff]], Stephen Colwell Associate Professor of Christian Ethics at [[Princeton Theological Seminary]]\n* [[Scott Eder]], sports executive, marathoner and triathlete\n* [[Larry Fedora]], former head football coach at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]\n* [[Maurice Harper]], American football player\n* [[David Lee \"Tex\" Hill]], World War II triple ace, member of the Flying Tigers. John Wayne based his character on Hill in the movie ''Flying Tigers''<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120316161313/http://obit.porterloring.com/obitdisplay.html?id=465501&listing=All</ref>\n* [[John Hitt]], president of the [[University of Central Florida]]\n* [[Ron Kirk]], former Mayor of Dallas and former [[United States Trade Representative]]\n* [[Candace Kita]], actress\n* [[Haskell Monroe]], notable educator and university administrator\n* [[Ray Morehart]], baseball player, [[Chicago White Sox]], [[New York Yankees]], played with [[Babe Ruth]] and [[Lou Gehrig]]\n* [[John O. Moseley|John Moseley]], educator and college president\n* [[David Peeples]], Texas state court judge since 1981, based in San Antonio\n* [[Carroll Pickett]], Presbyterian minister, author and advocate for abolishing the death penalty<ref name=\"Within\">Stowers, Carlton, and [[Carroll Pickett]], ''Within These Walls: Memoirs of a Death House Chaplain'', {{ISBN|978-0-312-28717-7}}, [[St. Martin's Press]], 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JQlIcYytPmkC Google Books]</ref>\n* [[Homer Rainey]], college president and professor\n* [[Charlie Robertson]], [[Major League Baseball|American Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n* [[Walter E. Rogers|Walter Rogers]], [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]]\n* [[Dan Stoenescu]], Romanian diplomat and former Minister for Romanians Abroad \n* [[Vern Sutton]], operatic tenor\n* [[Tom Thompson (American football)|Tom Thompson]], NCAA Football record holder\n* [[Larry Tidwell]], head women's basketball coach at NCAA Division I programs [[Lamar University]] and [[University of Texas\u2013Pan American]].\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*[[Light Townsend Cummins]], (State Historian of Texas, Texas history author)\n*[[George Diggs]], (biologist, Texas flora)\n*[[Joseph Havel]], (Artist, Current Director, [[Glassell School of Art]])\n*[[Jerry B. Lincecum]], (English, Texas folklore author)\n*[[Shelton Williams]], (political science/international studies, government consultant)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Austin College}}\n* {{Official website|www.austincollege.edu}}\n*[http://www.acroos.com Official athletics website]\n{{Education in Grayson County, Texas}}\n{{Private colleges and universities in Texas}}\n{{Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Presbyterian Colleges}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{coord|33|38|49.22|N|96|35|50.16|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Austin College| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Texas]]\n[[Category:Education in Grayson County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Presbyterian Church (USA)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Grayson County, Texas]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic Association of the Red River]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = Austin College\n|image = \n|motto       = ''Nil nisi per aspera''\n|mottoeng    = ''Nothing but the fierce''\n|established = 1849\n|type        = [[Private university|Private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]]\n|affiliation = [[Presbyterian Church USA|Presbyterian]]\n|endowment   = [[United States dollar|$]]133 million<ref>As of November, 2014.  {{cite web | title = Austin College: Adding Value to a Changing World Strategic Plan 2015-2020| publisher = Austin College | url = http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/StrategicPlan-2015-2020.pdf| format = PDF | accessdate = November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n|president   = Steven O'Day\n|students  = 1,223 (2019)<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543 U. S. News]</ref>\n|city        = [[Sherman, Texas|Sherman]]\n|state       = [[Texas]]\n|country     = United States\n|campus      = [[Suburban]], {{convert|70|acre}} \n|free_label  = \n|free        = \n|athletics   = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference|SCAC]] <br/> ''Compete in the [[Southern Athletic Association]] for football''\n|colors      = Crimson & Gold<ref>http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/Brand-Guide-2014.pdf</ref><br/>{{color box|#981E32}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FDB913}}&nbsp;\n|nickname    = Kangaroos, The Fighting 'Roos\n|mascot      = [[Kangaroo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acroos.com/sports/cheer/mascot|title=The Kangaroo Mascot|work=Austin College}}</ref>\n|website= {{url|www.austincollege.edu}}\n|staff       = 104\n|academic_affiliations= [[Oberlin Group]]<br>[[Annapolis Group]]<br>[[Council of Independent Colleges|CIC]]<br>[[Association of Presbyterian Colleges and Universities|APCU]]\n| logo = Austin College logo.svg\n}}\n\n[[File:AdminAC.JPG|thumb|right|Administrative building]]\n\n'''Austin College''' is a [[private university|private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] affiliated with the [[Presbyterian Church (USA)]] and located in [[Sherman, Texas]].<ref name=\"Austin College History\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/about/history/ Austin College], Austin College History.</ref>\n\nAbout 1,300 students are enrolled at the college.<ref name=\"Austin College Life\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/prospective-students/life-at-austin-college/ Austin College] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611143303/http://www.austincollege.edu/prospective-students/life-at-austin-college/ |date=June 11, 2011 }}, Austin College Life.</ref> Students are required to live on campus for the first three years of their education in order to foster a close-knit and community oriented campus lifestyle. Austin College actively promotes [[study abroad]] programs; 70% of graduates have at least one international study experience during college, and about 82% of students are involved in research.<ref name=\"austincollege.edu1\">http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/ACDifference_Bookmark_2013.pdf</ref> The college cultivates close interaction between students and professors via a 13:1<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://premium.usnews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543/rankings|title=Indicator|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> student to faculty ratio and an average class size of fewer than 25 students.<ref name=\"Austin College Faculty\">[http://www.austincollege.edu/academics/faculty/ Austin College], Austin College Faculty.</ref> The college has no teaching assistants, so regular faculty teach all levels of coursework.\n\nChartered in November 1849, Austin College remains the oldest institution of higher education in Texas to be operating under its original charter and name as recognized by the [[Texas Historical Commission|State Historical Survey Committee]].<ref name=\"Austin College History\"/> The college was profiled in all three editions of ''[[Colleges That Change Lives]]''.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Main.GIF|thumb|Old Main]]\nThe college was founded on October 13, 1849, in [[Huntsville, Texas]], by the [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College|Hampden\u2013Sydney]]<ref>{{cite web| title = An Army of Good Men| work = The Record| publisher = Hampden\u2013Sydney College| url = http://www.hsc.edu/The-Record/2010-September/An-army-of-good-men.html| access-date = 2014-04-02| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120111130039/http://www.hsc.edu/The-Record/2010-September/An-army-of-good-men.html| archive-date = 2012-01-11| url-status = dead}}</ref> and [[Princeton University|Princeton]]-educated missionary Dr. Daniel Baker. Signed by Texas Governor [[George Tyler Wood|George Wood]], the charter of Austin College was modeled after those of [[Harvard University|Harvard]], [[Yale University|Yale]], and [[Princeton University|Princeton]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = History|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/about/history/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\nBaker named the school for the Texas historical figure [[Stephen F. Austin]] after the original land on which it was built was donated by the Austin family. Two other important figures in Texas history, [[Sam Houston]] and [[Anson Jones]],<ref name=\"Austin College History\" /> served on the original board of trustees for the college, and the former site in Huntsville later became today's [[Sam Houston State University]].\n\nAustin College's founding president was Irish-born Presbyterian minister [[Samuel McKinney]], who served as the school's president a second time from 1862 to 1871.<ref name=\"amelia\">{{cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fmc74 |title= MCKINNEY, SAMUEL | first= Amelia W. | last=Williams | date= June 15, 2010| website= Handbook of Texas Online | publisher = [[Texas State Historical Association]] |access-date= September 6, 2015}}</ref> Under the tenure of the fourth president of Austin College, Reverend Samuel Magoffin Luckett,<ref name=\":0\" /> Austin College suffered several [[yellow fever]] epidemics and complications related to [[American Civil War|the Civil War]]. Texas Synod of the Presbyterian Church decided the college would be relocated to Sherman in 1876. Construction of the new campus in north Texas came in the form of \"Old Main,\" a two-story, red brick structure, which occurred between 1876 and 1878. Struggling with the [[Long Depression]]. Austin College saw little improvement to its building or grounds during the late 1870s; as such, Samuel Luckett resigned his position as president. From 1878 to 1885, the college continued to struggle from the aftershocks of economic depression; with an increasing debt and shrinking student body, the college turned to its 7th president, Reverend Donald MacGregor. A shrewd and well connected businessman, President MacGregor relieved a great deal of the college's debt and returned operations to normalcy. After MacGregor's death in 1887, the college welcomed President Luckett back to the campus. Throughout his second term as president, Samuel Luckett adopted a military program, grew the student body, introduced a YMCA chapter, established intercollegiate athletics and Greek fraternities, and added two wings to Old Main.\n\nOne of the school's most iconic presidents came in the form of Reverend Thomas Stone Clyce, who served as the Austin College president from 1900 to 1931; Reverend Clyce's presidency would become, and remains, the longest tenure in Austin College history.\n\nOn January 21 of 1913, Old Main was set ablaze and burnt to the ground in a matter of hours. A professor of Austin College, Davis Foute Eagleton described the incident: {{quote|\"''Austin College on fire and every particle of wood reduced to ashes--and walls rendered totally unfit for use. Oh, dies irae, dies irae! - The dear old building in which I have laboured for twenty-four years, gone! What traditions, memories, griefs, joys, were associated with it! The carpenters were approaching the completion of their work. The new English room was completed, the library room was soon to be ready. The literary societies lost everything. I lost all books, or, [those] in my class room. The laboratories were almost a total loss. Fortunately, the library, records, and office furniture were all in the new Y.M.C.A. building. Before the fire had begun to die out, the Senior class called the student body together and they pledged themselves by classes in writing to stand by the Faculty and the College, and that no one would leave. The Faculty also met shortly after and unanimously decided to continue college work the next day as usual, meeting their classes in places designated. Probably not another institution in the State could have done this.'' ''But the old College building is gone forever!!!\"''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lost Buildings of Austin College 1|url = http://abell.austincollege.edu/visitors/welcome/lost/lostm.html|website = abell.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150908033645/http://abell.austincollege.edu/visitors/welcome/lost/lostm.html|archive-date = 2015-09-08|url-status = dead}}</ref>}}Following the fire, the citizens of Sherman raised $50,000 to help the college rebuild. Now one of the oldest buildings on the Austin College campus, Sherman Hall housed administrative offices, an auditorium-chapel, and a library. Now the home of the [[humanities]] division, Sherman Hall boasted such guests as [[Harry Houdini]], [[Harry Blackstone, Sr.|Harry Blackstone Sr]]., [[Ernestine Schumann-Heink|Madame Schumann-Heink]], [[William Howard Taft]], and [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]].\n\nTo this day, the Austin College administration rarely cancels classes for weather or minor incidents in honor of the great commitment students and faculty made to continue on with regular coursework following the fire.\n\nAustin College became co-educational in 1918, merging in 1930 with the all-female [[Texas Presbyterian College]].\n\n[[Great Depression in the United States|The Great Depression]] severely limited campus growth and educational expansion, however the college quickly regained momentum in the mid-1930s with the introduction of many courses, ground breaking on new facilities, and growth of previously established programs. Throughout 1942, Austin College trained some 300 men and women in engineering, science and management courses as part of the United States Office of Education's war efforts. The following year, Austin College undertook a Cadet nurses training program and hosted Naval Reserves, Texas Home Guard, Army-air trainees and Air Corps Cadets.\n\nOn September 20, 1973, the musician [[Jim Croce]] died in a [[plane crash]] in [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]], on his way to perform the next night at Austin College. Six people died in the crash.\n\nIn 1994, Dr. Oscar Page joined the community as its 14th president. Under his tenure, 1994-2009, Dr. Page increased the school's endowment by nearly 80%, due in large part to his dedicated fundraising efforts as evidenced by the success of the \"Campaign for the New Era;\" a total of $120 million were raised and the campaign was heralded as the largest fundraiser in Austin College's history. Dr. Page orchestrated the construction of Jordan Family Language House, Jerry E. Apple Stadium, the Robert J. and Mary Wright Campus Center, the Robert M. and Joyce A. Johnson 'Roo Suites, and the Betsy Dennis Forster Art Studio Complex; as well as the renovation of  the David E. and Cassie L. Temple Center for Teaching and Learning at Thompson House and of Wortham Center, and creation of the John A. and Katherine G. Jackson Technology Center, the Margaret Binkley Collins and William W. Collins, Jr., Alumni Center, and the College Green in Honor of John D. and Sara Bernice Moseley and Distinguished Faculty.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = Past Presidents|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/about/office-of-the-president/past-presidents/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn the latter part of Austin College's history, the school would see de-segregation, welcome its first full-time black faculty member, first female head of a department, and, employ its first female president.\n\nDr. Marjorie Hass joined the campus in 2009 as both its first female and [[Jewish faith]] president. Under her leadership, the college saw the construction of the IDEA Center and two new housing complexes\u2014the Flats at Brockett Court and the Village on Grand. The IDEA Center is a 103,000 square ft. facility which includes multi-disciplinary and multi-purpose classrooms, laboratories, lecture halls and the largest telescope in the region found in Adams Observatory. It is  a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Gold certified facility.<ref>{{Cite web|title = IDEA Center|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/campus-offices/business-affairs/physical-plant/idea/|website = www.austincollege.edu|accessdate = 2015-11-12}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nOn August 17, 2017 Austin College announced its 16th President, Steven P. O'Day, J.D., former vice president of strategic initiatives at [[Lebanon Valley College]]. O'Day took office on October 30, 2017.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes        = 250\n| USNWR_LA      = 117\n| Wamo_LA       = 116\n}}\nListed in the [[U.S. News & World Report]] \"Guide to the 331 Most Interesting Colleges\", Austin College is ranked #117 on the 2019 list of National Liberal Arts Colleges. Austin College was ranked 79th in 2016. President O'Day took office in 2017, and Austin College slipped to 117th in 2020, the lowest ranking National Liberal Arts College in Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/austin-college-3543/rankings?int=c6b9e3| title=Austin College| publisher=U.S. News}}</ref>  The school is named a Best Western College by [[The Princeton Review]] and is also included in The Princeton Review's Best 377 Colleges. Austin College has been ranked as one of the top ten colleges in Texas by [[USA Today]], College Factual, and Best Colleges.\n\nAustin College is a member of the International 50, a group of the top colleges in the US for international focus, the non-profit organization Colleges That Change Lives and is one of the original 40 colleges profiled in the book [[Colleges That Change Lives|Colleges That Change Lives: 40 Schools That Will Change the Way You Feel About Colleges]] by Loren Pope.\n\n==Academics==\nAustin College offers about 35 majors and pre-professional programs for study, and students can also create a specialized major to match their academic interests. The college is known for its nationally recognized five-year Master of Arts in Teaching program, its pre-medical, international studies, and pre-law programs, which draw many students to the campus. The college has a music program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austincollege.edu/music|title=music program|work=austincollege.edu}}</ref> and supports the Austin College A Cappella Choir and the Sherman Symphony Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shermansymphony.com|title=www.shermansymphony.com|work=shermansymphony.com}}</ref> made up of students and local musicians, and assorted smaller musical ensembles. It sponsors the Posey Center of Excellence in Leadership, the Center for Environmental Studies, and the Center for Southwestern and Mexican Studies, three specialized programs that give students numerous research and internship opportunities. The school also has active programs in over 40 academic disciplines. The school's student newspaper, the Austin College ''Observer'', is a bi-weekly publication.\n\n==Athletics==\nAustin College participates in [[NCAA Division III]] athletics. Previously, Austin College competed in NAIA Division II athletics. Austin College athletes do not receive athletic scholarships.  The football team became known as the \"Kangaroos\" sometime during the 1914 to 1915 seasons. According to campus legend, the mascot name was derived from a kangaroo court of organized students that would paddle violators of college rules. Currently students refer to their sports teams as the 'fighting roos.'\n\nKangaroo varsity teams include American football, men and women's soccer, men's and women's cross country, volleyball, men's and women's basketball, swimming and diving, tennis, baseball, softball, and men's and women's water polo. More than 225 student athletics participate in varsity intercollegiate athletics each year. In 2004-2005, 28 students were recognized with all-conference athletic honors and 61 students received all-conference academic honors.\n\nAustin College joined the [[Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference|Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference (SCAC)]] on July 1, 2006, replacing [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]]. Austin College was previously a member of the [[American Southwest Conference]] (ASC), Texas Intercollegiate Athletic Association, and Texas Conference. In 2017, the Austin College football team joined the Southern Athletic Association in football, while remaining a member of the SCAC across all other sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acroos.com/sports/fball/2015-16/releases/20151117uguu1z|title=Austin College Football to Join SAA as Affiliate Member|author=|date=18 November 2015|website=acroos.com}}</ref> The college started fielding varsity men's and women's water polo during the 2018-19 school year; the men participate in the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation (MPSF) while the women compete in [[Collegiate Water Polo Association]] (CWPA) Division III.\n\n=== Baseball ===\nIn 2007, the first year of participating in the SCAC, the Austin College baseball team won the conference tournament, beating Millsaps College 9-7 in the finals. The Roos finished the season with a win-loss record of 22-25. The tournament win was the first ever conference championship for the Roos and the first time the program had ever been in the Regional tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.austincollege.edu/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/acmagazine_june07.pdf|title = Austin College Magazine|date = June 2007|access-date = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> [[Carl Iwasaki]] was the head coach for the Roos from 2005 until 2010.  He won two coach of the year awards, the first in 2006 while the Roos were still in the ASC and the second, coming in 2007 after the Roos had joined the SCAC. Coach Iwasaki was replaced by James Rise for the 2011 season who coached for four seasons. Under Rise, the Roos went  11-24 in 2011, 8-29 in 2012, 12-29 in 2013, and 6-33 in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = SCAC|url = http://scacsports.com/information/archives/index2|website = scacsports.com|access-date = 2016-01-22}}</ref> In the fall of 2014, the Roos hired Mike Ramsey, a former TCU baseball player, who in his first year went 8-21.\n\n=== Football ===\nAustin College began its first football season in 1896, making Austin College one of the first teams in the south. Austin College has had 119 straight seasons with a football team. Since its beginning Austin college has won eight conference championships, and one national championship. It has also hosted over 130 all Americans. Currently the football team is coached by Loren Dawson and is currently a member of [[NCAA Division III]] Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference (SCAC). As noted above, the football team moved to the Southern Athletic Association (SAA) in 2017.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Ryan Allen]], opera singer\n* [[Marshall Applewhite]], leader of the Heaven's Gate religious cult.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news| date=1997-03-29| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D07E5DC133AF93AA15750C0A961958260| publisher=New York Times| title=From Religious Childhood To Reins of a U.F.O. Cult| accessdate=2008-05-08 | first=Jacques | last=Steinberg}}</ref>\n* [[Gene Babb]], President, National Football Scouting Inc.; former player for the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Houston Oilers]] and [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n* [[Thomas Henry Ball]], Texas politician and member of the [[United States House of Representatives]]\n* [[Smith Ballew]], actor and singer\n* [[Billy Bookout]], American football player\n* [[Hannibal Boone]], 16th Attorney General of Texas\n* [[Byron Boston]], a football official in the [[National Football League]]\n* [[Joe Coomer (American football)|Joe Coomer]], American football player\n* [[Deborah Crombie]], New York Times bestselling author.\n* [[Philip N. Diehl|Philip Diehl]], Director of the [[United States Mint]]. \n* [[Nancy J. Duff|Nancy Duff]], Stephen Colwell Associate Professor of Christian Ethics at [[Princeton Theological Seminary]]\n* [[Scott Eder]], sports executive, marathoner and triathlete\n* [[Larry Fedora]], former head football coach at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]\n* [[Maurice Harper]], American football player\n* [[David Lee \"Tex\" Hill]], World War II triple ace, member of the Flying Tigers. John Wayne based his character on Hill in the movie ''Flying Tigers''<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120316161313/http://obit.porterloring.com/obitdisplay.html?id=465501&listing=All</ref>\n* [[John Hitt]], president of the [[University of Central Florida]]\n* [[Ron Kirk]], former Mayor of Dallas and former [[United States Trade Representative]]\n* [[Candace Kita]], actress\n* [[Haskell Monroe]], notable educator and university administrator\n* [[Ray Morehart]], baseball player, [[Chicago White Sox]], [[New York Yankees]], played with [[Babe Ruth]] and [[Lou Gehrig]]\n* [[John O. Moseley|John Moseley]], educator and college president\n* [[David Peeples]], Texas state court judge since 1981, based in San Antonio\n* [[Carroll Pickett]], Presbyterian minister, author and advocate for abolishing the death penalty<ref name=\"Within\">Stowers, Carlton, and [[Carroll Pickett]], ''Within These Walls: Memoirs of a Death House Chaplain'', {{ISBN|978-0-312-28717-7}}, [[St. Martin's Press]], 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=JQlIcYytPmkC Google Books]</ref>\n* [[Homer Rainey]], college president and professor\n* [[Charlie Robertson]], [[Major League Baseball|American Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n* [[Walter E. Rogers|Walter Rogers]], [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]]\n* [[Dan Stoenescu]], Romanian diplomat and former Minister for Romanians Abroad \n* [[Vern Sutton]], operatic tenor\n* [[Tom Thompson (American football)|Tom Thompson]], NCAA Football record holder\n* [[Larry Tidwell]], head women's basketball coach at NCAA Division I programs [[Lamar University]] and [[University of Texas\u2013Pan American]].\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*[[Light Townsend Cummins]], (State Historian of Texas, Texas history author)\n*[[George Diggs]], (biologist, Texas flora)\n*[[Joseph Havel]], (Artist, Current Director, [[Glassell School of Art]])\n*[[Jerry B. Lincecum]], (English, Texas folklore author)\n*[[Shelton Williams]], (political science/international studies, government consultant)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Austin College}}\n* {{Official website|www.austincollege.edu}}\n*[http://www.acroos.com Official athletics website]\n{{Education in Grayson County, Texas}}\n{{Private colleges and universities in Texas}}\n{{Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Presbyterian Colleges}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{coord|33|38|49.22|N|96|35|50.16|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Austin College| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Texas]]\n[[Category:Education in Grayson County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1849]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Presbyterian Church (USA)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Grayson County, Texas]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Texas]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic Association of the Red River]]\n", "name_user": "ElKevbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin_College"}
{"title_page": "Sex and Love", "text_new": "{{other uses of}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Sex and Love\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Enrique Iglesias]]\n| cover      = Sex and Love.png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|2014|03|14}}\n| recorded   = 2012\u201314\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Latin pop]]<ref>[http://www.popmatters.com/review/180038-enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love/ Enrique Iglesias: SEX AND LOVE &#124; PopMatters] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320125740/http://www.popmatters.com/review/180038-enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love/ |date=20 March 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[electropop]]\n* [[dance-pop]]<ref>[http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-review-slick-spanglish-dance-pop-1.7394863 Enrique Iglesias' 'Sex and Love' review: Slick, Spanglish dance pop - Newsday] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420050457/http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-review-slick-spanglish-dance-pop-1.7394863 |date=20 April 2014 }}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=38|s=06}}\n| language   = {{flatlist|\n* English\n* Spanish\n* Portuguese\n}}\n| label      = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[The Cataracs]]\n* Mark Taylor\n* Carlos Paucar\n* [[DJ Frank E]]\n* Descemer Bueno\n* [[RedOne]]\n* [[Marty James]]\n* [[Rome Ramirez|Rome]]\n* Metrophonic\n* [[Romeo Santos]]\n* [[soFLY & Nius]]\n* [[Alex P]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Euphoria (Enrique Iglesias album)|Euphoria]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Sex and Love\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Finally Found You]]\n | single1date = 17 September 2012\n | single2     = [[Turn the Night Up]]\n | single2date = 15 July 2013\n | single3     = [[Loco (Enrique Iglesias song)|Loco]]\n | single3date = 26 August 2013\n | single4     = [[Heart Attack (Enrique Iglesias song)|Heart Attack]]\n | single4date = 16 September 2013\n | single5     = [[El Perdedor (Enrique Iglesias song)|El Perdedor]]\n | single5date = 28 October 2013\n | single6     = [[I'm a Freak]]\n | single6date = 13 January 2014\n | single7     = [[Bailando (Enrique Iglesias song)|Bailando]]\n | single7date = 3 February 2014\n | single8     = [[Noche y De D\u00eda]]\n | single8date = 5 January 2015\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Sex and Love''''' is the tenth [[studio album]] recorded by Spanish recording artist [[Enrique Iglesias]]. It was released on 14 March 2014 by [[Republic Records]]. The album's three Spanish singles: \"[[Loco (Enrique Iglesias song)|Loco]]\", \"[[El Perdedor (Enrique Iglesias song)|El Perdedor]]\" and \"[[Bailando (Enrique Iglesias song)|Bailando]]\" reached No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart. The album features guest vocals from [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Descemer Bueno]], [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]], [[Flo Rida]], Anthony Touma, [[Romeo Santos]], [[Mickael Carreira]], [[Marco Antonio Sol\u00eds]], [[Yandel]], [[Gente de Zona]], [[Luan Santana]], [[India Mart\u00ednez]] and [[Sean Paul]]. ''Sex and Love'' won the [[Lo Nuestro Award for Pop Album of the Year]].\n\n==Background==\nIn an interview Enrique explained the reason behind titling his new album as ''Sex and Love''. He said: \"It's one of the first things I thought about when I listened to the whole body of work. I think it's something we can all relate to no matter what religion no matter what personality, no matter what colour we can all relate to it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv3.ie/entertainment_article.php?locID=1.803.810&article=126162 |title=Enrique Iglesias thinks legs are sexy - TV3 Xpos\u00e9 Entertainment |publisher=Tv3.ie |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nSpeaking about his album Enrique described his album as fun and obviously sexual, while some of it is more introspective and nostalgic. He then went on to say: \"The words go together, but they can be separate and inspire different feelings and thoughts. It's all-encompassing. When you turn on the radio, what are the themes that everybody relates to? We all relate to sex and love. That's why when you hear music&nbsp;\u2013 90% of the time&nbsp;\u2013 it derives from those two feelings.\"{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Release and promotion==\nThis album became available for pre-order on 15 February 2014 through [[Topspin Media]]. Two versions of the album (the standard containing 11 tracks and the deluxe with 5 bonus tracks) are available, both physically and digitally.<ref name=\"Pre-order\">{{cite web | url=http://labs.topspin.net/artists/enriqueiglesias/sexandlove/ | title=Enrique Iglesias Sex & Love | publisher=Topspin Media | date=15 February 2014 | accessdate=15 February 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225034517/http://labs.topspin.net/artists/enriqueiglesias/sexandlove/ | archivedate=25 February 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Pre-order%2520Announcenent%2520on%2520Facebook%2520\">{{cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/Enrique/photos/a.128331853123.105821.19061333123/10152035990743124/?type=1&stream_ref=10 | title=#SEXANDLOVE album pre-order is live | publisher=Facebook | work=Enrique Iglesias | date=15 February 2014 | accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> A special deluxe edition for [[Target Corporation|Target]] and [[Walmart]] is also available, which contains two bonus tracks. The album became available for pre-order via iTunes in the United States, Canada and Mexico on 4 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/sex-and-love/id829282622 |title=iTunes - Music - SEX AND LOVE by Enrique Iglesias |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref> The pre-order was available for rest of the world on 5 March 2014. A 30-second sample was released on iTunes for each track.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 54/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/sex-and-love/enrique-iglesias|title=Reviews for Sex and love by Enrique Iglesias}}</ref>\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |title=Review: ''Sex And Love'' |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=mw0002619796|pure_url=yes}} |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[ArtistDirect]]\n| rev2Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: ''Sex And Love, A Masterpiece by Enrique'' |url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-album-review-5-out-of-5-stars/10916832|publisher=[[Artistdirect]] |accessdate=24 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325102808/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-album-review-5-out-of-5-stars/10916832|archivedate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n|rev3       = ''[[The Boston Globe]]''\n|rev3score  = (favorable)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2014/03/17/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love/NKqRBcgcxjTdSn7m6tKWXO/story.html|title=Enrique Iglesias, \"Sex And Love\"|publisher=Boston Globe|accessdate=18 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320142820/http://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2014/03/17/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love/NKqRBcgcxjTdSn7m6tKWXO/story.html|archivedate=20 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev4      = [[Speakeasy Mag|Culture Fix]]\n| rev4Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"culturefix\">{{cite web |title=Review: ''Sex And Love'' |url=http://www.culturefix.co.uk/2014/03/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-love.html|publisher=Culture Fix|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325203944/http://www.culturefix.co.uk/2014/03/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-love.html|archivedate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev5      = ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: ''Sex And Love'' |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz/playlist/369841/Leading-by-Example-This-week-s-big-single-and-album-releases|publisher=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]] |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6      = [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]\n| rev6Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: ''Sex And Love'' |url=http://www.idolator.com/7510262/enrique-iglesias-sex-love-album-review|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=18 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318153440/http://www.idolator.com/7510262/enrique-iglesias-sex-love-album-review|archivedate=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev7      = ''[[Jake Hamilton|Jake's Take]]''\n| rev7Score = (B)<ref>{{cite web |title=Enrique's Sex And Love (2014)|url=http://jakes-take.com/2014/03/new-music-releases-week-of-march-17-2014|accessdate=17 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318232045/http://jakes-take.com/2014/03/new-music-releases-week-of-march-17-2014/|archivedate=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n| rev8      = ''[[Newsday]]''\n| rev8Score = (B)<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |title=Sex And Love (2014) - Enrique Iglesias |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-review-slick-spanglish-dance-pop-1.7394863|accessdate=17 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420050457/http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love-review-slick-spanglish-dance-pop-1.7394863|archivedate=20 April 2014}}</ref>\n| rev9      = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=Faulkner|first1=Brent|title=Enrique Iglesias: SEX AND LOVE|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/180038-enrique-iglesias-sex-and-love/|website=PopMatters|accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'' gave the album 3 out of 5 stars stating that \"Iglesias has turned all sleazy Robin Thicke slurring: 'I've been spending all my money on these pretty girls and alcohol, but honey, they got nothing on you' over the funky 'Let Me Be Your Lover'.\" However they praised \"Loco\", stating that it will have fans \"getting their Latin freak on\". ''AllMusic'' also gave the album 3/5, stating \"Iglesias walks the line between the dancefloor jams of 2007's ''Insomniac'' and the romantic flavor of 2010's ''Euphoria''.\" They chose \"Bailando\", \"El Perdedor\", \"Let Me Be Your Lover\" and \"Loco\" as the best songs from the album.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thom Jurek |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/sex-and-love-mw0002619796 |title=Sex and Love - Enrique Iglesias &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref> ''[[Newsday]]'' gave the album a \"B\" grade and described the album as \"slick, state-of-the-art Spanglish dance pop\". ''Idolator'' gave the album 3/5 stars and called the album ''[[Euphoria (Enrique Iglesias album)|Euphoria]]''{{'}}s \"older cousin\". They stated that the album isn't his greatest but there's enough decent material to remind you of what Enrique is capable of at full flight. They named \"You & I\" and \"Bailando\" as the best singles from the album.<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\nJake Hamilton of ''Jake's Take'' gave the album a \"B\" grade stating that he went overboard on the Spanish tracks. He also praised Iglesias work in co-writing every song on the album. [[The Boston Globe]] gave a favorable review stating that Enrique \"remains a heartthrob for a reason.\" They also said that \"You and I\" is \"filled with romantic yearning,\" while his duet with Kylie Minogue, \"Beautiful,\" \"manages to be corny yet endearing.\" They concluded that \"It\u2019s the heat not the beat that brings out the best in Iglesias.\" [[Artistdirect]] gave a positive review and gave the album 5/5 stars stating that the new album is Enrique's biggest and boldest masterpiece yet. They described the song \"Noche Y Dia\" as one of the most powerful and potent Latin anthems ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturefix.co.uk/2014/03/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-love.html |title=Album Review: Enrique Iglesias - Sex + Love |publisher=Culture Fix |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325203944/http://www.culturefix.co.uk/2014/03/album-review-enrique-iglesias-sex-love.html|archivedate=25 March 2014}}</ref> ''Culture Fix'' took note of the album's range of styles stating \"The club-friendly tracks are slickly produced and filled with a high-octane energy, the ballads are complete with a raw charisma and emotion, and the mid-tempo tracks hark back to some of the singer's best work,\" scoring the album 4/5.<ref name=\"culturefix\"/>\n\n===Commercial performance===\n''Sex and Love'' debuted at No. 8 on US ''Billboard'' 200, selling 24,000 copies in its first week. It is Iglesias's third ''Billboard'' top 10 album after ''[[Euphoria (Enrique Iglesias album)|Euphoria]]'' (No. 10) and ''[[Escape (Enrique Iglesias album)|Escape]]'' (No. 2).<ref>{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title='Frozen' Earns Its Biggest Sales Week Yet, Tops Billboard 200 a Seventh Time|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6006529/frozen-earns-its-biggest-sales-week-yet-tops-billboard-200-a-seventh-time|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> The album also entered the top 10 of the [[Canadian Albums Chart]]. It peaked at No. 1 on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|Top Latin Albums]] and [[Latin Pop Albums]] charts simultaneously. It peaked at No. 11 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], selling an approximate of 7,500 copies in first week. It also peaked at No. 6 on the [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|Spanish Albums Chart]]. The album received a gold certification within the second week of its release in Mexico. ''Sex and Love'' was certified double platinum by the [[RIAA]] in the Latin field for shipping over 120,000 copies; furthermore has sold 174,000 copies since its release in March in United States.<ref name=ussales>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6436399/nielsen-music-soundscan-2014-taylor-swift-republic-records-streaming?page=0%2C3|title=Music in 2014: Taylor Takes the Year, Republic Records on Top, Streaming to the Rescue|last=Christman|first=Ed|work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date= 9 January 2015 |accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\n* \"[[Finally Found You]]\" was released as a single on 17 September 2012. The track features vocals from rapper [[Sammy Adams]]. Commercially, the song managed to reach the top twenty in [[Canada]] and the top forty in [[Australia]], [[Spain]] and [[United States]], also topping the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart. However, this song was only included on the international deluxe edition of ''Sex and Love''. \n* \"[[Turn the Night Up]]\" was released as the second single from the album and the song debuted at number 30 on the [[Pop Songs]] chart and at number 6 on [[Dance/Electronic Digital Songs]], while also debuting at number 62 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. \n* \"[[Loco (Enrique Iglesias song)|Loco]]\" was released as the third single from the album and features guest vocals from Bachata singer [[Romeo Santos]]. The single reached No. 1 in Spain, Mexico and the Dominican Republic. Moreover, it also became Iglesias' 23rd No. 1 single on the Hot Latin Tracks chart and 18th No. 1 single on the Latin Pop Airplay chart. It was also ranked at No. 9 on the ''Billboard'' Year-End Hot Latin Songs chart for 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5748225/enrique-iglesias-widens-lead-for-most-no-1s-on-latin-songs |title=Enrique Iglesias Widens Lead for Most No. 1s on Hot Latin Songs Chart |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013004946/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5748225/enrique-iglesias-widens-lead-for-most-no-1s-on-latin-songs|archivedate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n* \"[[Heart Attack (Enrique Iglesias song)|Heart Attack]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album. It was released exclusively in North America. It peaked at No. 88 on US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and No. 83 on Canadian Hot 100. It also reached No. 26 on US Mainstream Top 40, making it Iglesias' 16th entry on that chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/301773/Enrique+Iglesias/chart?f=381 |title=Enrique Iglesias - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref> \n* \"[[El Perdedor (Enrique Iglesias song)|El Perdedor]]\" was released as the fifth single from the album. It features guest vocals from [[Marco Antonio Solis]]. It serves as the opening theme of Mexican telenovela ''[[Lo Que La Vida Me Rob\u00f3]]'' (2013-2014). This is the fifth time that Enrique's song is chosen as an opening theme of a telenovela after \"Cosas del Amor\", \"Nunca Te Olvidar\u00e9\", \"Cuando Me Enamoro\", \"Marisol\" (Por Amarte) and \"El Pa\u00eds de las Mujeres\" (Ruleta Rusa). It became Iglesias' 24th No. 1 single on the Hot Latin Songs chart and 19th No. 1 single on the Latin Pop Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5892790/enrique-iglesias-scores-24th-no-1-sex-love-album-art |title=Enrique Iglesias Scores 24th No. 1, Reveals Album Title 'Sex+Love' |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408213249/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/5892790/enrique-iglesias-scores-24th-no-1-sex-love-album-art|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref> \n* \"[[I'm a Freak]]\" was released as the sixth single from the album and the first one to be released worldwide. The song features Cuban-American rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]. The song became a commercial success in Europe peaking within the top ten in the United Kingdom, Spain, Ireland, Finland and Serbia. It peaked at No. 45 in Australia and No. 52 in Canada. It also peaked at No. 38 on US Mainstream Top 40 chart, making it Iglesias' 17th entry on that chart.\n* \"[[Bailando (Enrique Iglesias song)|Bailando]]\" was the seventh single to be released from the album.<ref name=chileoro>{{cite web|url=http://www.carolina.cl/musica/2014/04/enrique-iglesias-presenta-su-nuevo-single-bailando/|title=Enrique Iglesias presenta su nuevo single \"Bailando\"|publisher=Carolina 99.3|language=Spanish|accessdate=8 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408225031/http://www.carolina.cl/musica/2014/04/enrique-iglesias-presenta-su-nuevo-single-bailando/|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref> It became Iglesias' 25th No. 1 single on the Hot Latin Songs chart and 20th No. 1 single on the Latin Pop Airplay chart. It holds the number 38 spot on the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 2014]] chart. The Spanish version of the song acts as the opening theme of telenovela Reina de Corazones.\n* \"[[Noche y De D\u00eda]]\" was released as an eighth and final single on 1 April 2015 and was certified platinum in Spain and gold in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/cl/album/Noche-y-dia-feat.-yandel-juan/id979220399?%7c=en|title=iTunes - M\u00fasica - Noche y de D\u00eda (feat. Yandel & Juan Magan) - Single de Enrique Iglesias|work=iTunes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B00V7BFI9Y?ie=UTF8&at=&force-full-site=1&ref_=aw_bottom_links|title=Noche Y De Dia [feat. Juan Magan]|work=amazon.de}}</ref> It will be officially sent to radio stations in Italy on 3 July 2015.<ref>http://www.radioairplay.fm/radio-date/ENRIQUE-IGLESIAS--Noche-Y-De-Dia-(feat.-Yandel-&-JUan-Magan)-133637-03-07-2015</ref>\n* \"[[Beautiful (Enrique Iglesias and Kylie Minogue song)|Beautiful]]\", featuring [[Kylie Minogue]], was released as the first promotional single on 14 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/beautiful-feat.-kylie-minogue/id839853131|title=iTunes - Music - Beautiful (feat. Kylie Minogue) - Single by Enrique Iglesias|work=iTunes}}</ref> \n*\"There Goes My Baby\" was released as the second promotional single only in the UK in May 2014.\n*\"Let Me Be Your Lover\", featuring Anthony Touma instead of Pitbull, was released as third promotional single in France on 22 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/fr/album/let-me-be-your-lover-feat./id929243070|title=iTunes - Musique - Let Me Be Your Lover (feat. Anthony Touma) [French Remix] - Single par Enrique Iglesias|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n\n===Other songs===\n\"[[I Like How It Feels]]\" was released as a digital download in Australia and some European countries on 23 September 2011. The song was released as a [[Music download|digital download]] in the United States on 4 October 2011. The song originally intended to be the lead single from a reissue of Iglesias' album ''[[Euphoria (Enrique Iglesias album)|Euphoria]]'', however, the release was cancelled after poor chart performance from the song. The song was later included on the international deluxe edition of ''Sex and Love''.\n\n==Tour==\n{{Main|Sex and Love Tour}}\nIglesias started a promo tour on 14 February 2014, which took place in San Juan, Puerto Rico.{{cn|date=March 2020}} The next day he performed at a sold-out concert at the [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/enrique-iglesias-set-heat-msg-valentine-weekend-concert-article-1.1612084 |title=Enrique Iglesias set to heat up Madison Square Garden with Valentine\u2019s weekend concert |publisher=NY Daily News |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014}}</ref> He is set to perform in Dia Anahuac, Mexico on 27 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Enrique Iglesias View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/mexico-dia-anahuac |title=Mexico - D\u00eda Anahuac - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302155331/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/mexico-dia-anahuac|archivedate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tour will officially kick-off from Santiago, [[Chile]], where Iglesias will perform on 20 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Zach from EI Team View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/santiago-chile |title=5/20 - Santiago, Chile - SEX AND LOVE TOUR - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407072517/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/santiago-chile|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref> Two days later on 22 May 2014 he performed  at [[Luna Park, Buenos Aires|Luna Park]] in Buenos Aires, Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Enrique Iglesias View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-22-buenos-aires-argentina-sex-and-love-tour |title=5/22 - Buenos Aires, Argentina - SEX AND LOVE TOUR - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date=2 April 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407073220/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-22-buenos-aires-argentina-sex-and-love-tour |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref> A second leg of the tour will visit North America in Fall 2014, and will be co-headlined by [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]. This is the second time that the two Latino stars have toured together with [[Euphoria Tour (Enrique Iglesias)|Euphoria Tour]] being their first.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/b/2014/03/18/pitbull-and-enrique-iglesias-announce-fall-2014-concert-tour.htm |title=Pitbull and Enrique Iglesias Announce Fall 2014 Concert Tour |publisher=Top40.about.com |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407065154/http://top40.about.com/b/2014/03/18/pitbull-and-enrique-iglesias-announce-fall-2014-concert-tour.htm |archivedate=7 April 2014 }}</ref>\nElsewhere he is performing in Mexico on 29 May 2014, 30 May 2014 and on 1 June 2014. [[Demi Lovato]] will be the opening act for few of the dates in the United Kingdom and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Enrique Iglesias View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-29-mexico-city-sex-and-love-tour |title=5/29 - Mexico City, Mexico - SEX AND LOVE TOUR - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075150/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-29-mexico-city-sex-and-love-tour|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Enrique Iglesias View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-30-mexico-city-mexico-sex-and-love-tour |title=5/30 - Mexico City, MEXICO - SEX AND LOVE TOUR - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075012/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/5-30-mexico-city-mexico-sex-and-love-tour|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Added by Enrique Iglesias View Events |url=http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/6-1-monterrey-sex-and-love-tour |title=6/1 - Monterrey, Mexico - SEX AND LOVE TOUR - Enrique Iglesias - Official Website |publisher=Enrique Iglesias |date= |accessdate=11 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075013/http://www.enriqueiglesias.com/events/6-1-monterrey-sex-and-love-tour|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\nEnrique Iglesias has grossed $194 million with Sex and Love Tour.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Sex and Love''&nbsp;\u2013 {{nobold|US standard version}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Enrique-Iglesias-Sex-And-Love/release/5963118 |title=Sex and Love, Enrique Iglesias: Pop |publisher=discogs.com |date=2014 |accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n| total_length    = 38:06\n| ext